{"title_page": "University of Toronto Faculty of Music", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name           = Faculty of Music\n| native_name    = \n| image_name     = \n| image_size     = \n| image_alt      = \n| caption        = \n| motto          = \n| motto_lang     = \n| motto_eng      = \n| former_names   = \n| established    = {{Start date|1918}}\n| closed         = \n| type           = [[Faculty (division)|Faculty]]\n| parent         = \n| affiliation    = [[University of Toronto]]\n| city           = [[Toronto]]\n| province       = [[Ontario]]\n| country        = [[Canada]]\n| coor           = {{coord|43.666717|N|79.394621|W|region:CA-ON_type:landmark_source:GoogleMaps|display=inline, title|format=dms}}\n| dean           = Don McLean\n| academic_staff = \n| administrative_staff = \n| students       = \n| undergrad      = \n| postgrad       = \n| doctoral       = \n| alumni         = \n| colours        = \n| symbol         = \n| website        = {{URL|www.music.utoronto.ca}}\n| logo           = [[File:University of Toronto Faculty of Music Black Logo.jpg|200px]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Faculty of Music at the University of Toronto''' is one of several professional faculties at the [[University of Toronto]]. The Faculty of Music is located at the Edward Johnson Building, just south of the [[Royal Ontario Museum]] and north of [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]], west of [[Museum (TTC)|Museum Subway Station]]. MacMillan Theatre and Walter Hall are located in the Edward Johnson Building. The Faculty of Music South building contains rehearsal rooms and offices, and the Upper Jazz Studio performance space is located at 90 Wellesley Street West. In 2011, the Faculty of Music hired Don McLean as the new Dean.\n\n==Historical timeline==\n\n*'''1844''' Music was considered a discipline worthy of recognition by the University of Toronto (named King's College until 1850) and examinations were held for candidates wishing to receive a degree in music.<ref name=Chandler>{{cite book|last=Chandler|first=Ron|title=Alumni Directory: Historical Introduction|year=1990|publisher=University of Toronto, Faculty of Music|location=Toronto|isbn=0-7727-8555-4|pages=4\u201335}}</ref>\n*'''1846''' James Paton Clarke became the first person in Canada to be awarded the degree of Bachelor of Music.<ref name=\"Canadian Encyclopedia\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=McMillan|first=Barclay|title=James Paton Clarke|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/james-paton-clarke|publisher=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|accessdate=6 December 2012}}</ref>\n*'''1858''' George Strathy received Canada's first D Mus at Trinity College.<ref name=Chandler /><ref name=\"Canadian Encyclopedia\">{{cite web|last=Green; Spier|first=J. Paul; Susan|title=Music at University of Toronto|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/emc/music-at-university-of-toronto|publisher=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=10 December 2012}}</ref>\n*'''1886''' [[The Royal Conservatory of Music|The Toronto Conservatory of Music]] was incorporated, and was operated in conjunction with the University of Toronto from its beginnings.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1904''' [[Trinity College, Toronto|Trinity College]] was relieved of the music degree, and the MusBac became a University of Toronto degree.<ref name=\"John Beckwith\">{{cite book|last=Beckwith|first=John|title=Music at Toronto: A Personal Account|year=1995|publisher=University of Toronto Press Incorporated|location=Toronto|isbn=0-9699416-0-9}}</ref>\n*'''1918''' The Faculty of Music was established. The Senate of the University withdrew its affiliations with various music schools ([[Toronto College of Music]] and [[Royal Hamilton College of Music]]) and inaugurated a Faculty of Music to teach music and administer examinations. Along with his duties as music director of the Toronto Conservatory, [[Augustus Stephen Vogt]] was appointed Dean.<ref name=Chandler /><ref name=\"Canadian Encyclopedia\" />\n*'''1921''' The Ontario Legislature passed Bill 154, an act that vested the assets of the Toronto Conservatory of Music in the University of Toronto.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1926''' [[Ernest MacMillan|Sir Ernest MacMillan]] became Dean of the Faculty of Music and Principal of the Toronto Conservatory of Music.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1934''' \u201cCourses of Instruction\u201d were introduced, the first courses to be taught at the Faculty.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1945''' [[Ettore Mazzoleni]] became Principal of the Conservatory. Edward Johnson was appointed to the Board of Governors of the University and the Conservatory.\n*'''1946''' [[Arnold Walter]] established and was appointed Director of the Senior School for advanced students at the Conservatory. He also established the three-year Artist Diploma program and the Opera School.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1947''' The Toronto Conservatory of Music received the Royal charter from [[George VI|King George VI]], and became The Royal Conservatory of Music.\n*'''1952-1953''' A new administrative structure was created \u2013 The Royal Conservatory of Music at the University of Toronto placed a Dean in charge of all music programs. There would be one Dean in charge of two divisions: The School of Music (the previous Royal Conservatory of Music) headed by a Principal (Ettore Mazzoleni) and the Faculty of Music, headed by a Director (Arnold Walter). The School of Music ran the opera school, examinations of grade 1 to ARCT, and the speech arts department. The Faculty of Music ran the Licentiate and Artist diploma courses, and the Senior School no longer existed. [[Boyd Neel]] was appointed Dean of the 'umbrella' RCMT.<ref name=Chandler /><ref name=\"Canadian Encyclopedia\" />\n*'''1954''' The first program for the Master of Music was introduced.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1958-1959''' The University's President's Report announced that the Faculty of Music would have a new building and the School of Music would move to McMaster Hall on Bloor Street.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1959''' Plans for an electronic music studio were announced, historically the second in a North American university.\n*'''1961-1962''' The MusBac became a four-year program.\n*'''1962''' The Faculty of Music moved to the newly built Edward Johnson Building (the first building in Canada designed specifically for professional music study), though the official opening was delayed until spring 1964, and the School of Music moved to McMaster Hall.\n*'''1966-1967''' The first Bachelor of Music in Performance was offered.\n*'''1969''' The Opera School transferred to the Faculty of Music and a two-year opera diploma program was approved.\n*'''1969-1970''' A new curriculum was put into place \u2013 \u2018basic music\u2019 subjects in the first two years were common to all students. The Master of Music in Performance was approved.\n*'''1970''' [[John Beckwith (composer)|John Beckwith]] was appointed Dean. The post of Director of the Faculty of Music was eliminated. The Faculty became responsibility of the Dean, and the School of Music was renamed to its more popular name, the Royal Conservatory of Music.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1973-1974''' This was the last year Conservatory performance certificates were accepted as alternatives for admission to the Faculty of Music. All incoming students were subsequently auditioned and interviewed.<ref name=\"John Beckwith\"/>\n*'''1977''' [[Gustav Ciamaga]] appointed Dean\n*'''1978-1979''' Theory and Conducting majors were added to the undergraduate curriculum. The conducting major was discontinued in 1986.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1979-1980''' The first jazz courses were offered.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1983-1984''' The University created the Committee on the Future of Music Studies to review how the faculty and conservatory were operated and organized. In 1984, its final report recommended the eventual separation of the Conservatory from the University.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1984''' Carl Morey appointed Dean.\n*'''1990''' [[Paul Pedersen (composer)|Paul Pedersen]] appointed Dean.\n*'''1991''' The Royal Conservatory of Music Act of the Ontario Legislature confirms the separation of the Conservatory from the University of Toronto and re-established The Royal Conservatory's status as a fully independent, not-for-profit entity. The MusBac in Jazz Performance is introduced.<ref name=\"Canadian Encyclopedia\" />\n*'''1996''' David Beach appointed Dean.\n*'''2004''' Gage Averill appointed Dean.\n*'''2007''' Russell Hartenberger was appointed Interim Dean and named Dean in 2008.\n*'''2007''' Concurrent Teacher's Education Program established, as well as the Doctorate in Musical Arts (DMA) in Performance.\n*'''2011''' Don McLean appointed Dean.\n\n==Research and collaborations==\n\n===Research institutes===\nThe Music and Health Research Collaboratory (MaHRC), established in 2012, is a collaborative group of researchers that aims to better understand the role of sound in human experiences, exploring connections of sound to the human experience of health.\n\nThe Institute for Canadian Music, established in 1984, aims to promote and support all areas of Canadian Music Study.\n\n===Artists in residence===\n* [[Canadian Brass]] - Distinguished Ensemble in Residence 2011-2015\n* Cecilia String Quartet - Ensemble in Residence\n* [[Gryphon Trio]] - Artists in Residence\n* [[Nexus (percussion ensemble)|Nexus]] - Resident Percussion Ensemble\n* [[Tafelmusik Baroque Orchestra|Tafelmusik]] - Baroque Orchestra in Residence\n* Young Voices Toronto (formerly High Park Choirs of Toronto) - Children's Choir in Residence\n* [[St. Lawrence String Quartet]] - Visiting Chamber Ensemble\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:EdwardJohnsonBuilding2.jpg|thumb|Edward Johnson Building]]\n'''Edward Johnson Building''' \u2013 Home of the Faculty of Music since 1962, the Edward Johnson Building houses many offices and classrooms, as well as two floors of practice rooms, two large rehearsal rooms, the Faculty of Music Library, the University of Toronto Electronic Music Studio (UTEMS), a theatre for large ensemble performances (MacMillan Theatre) and a smaller recital hall (Walter Hall), and named for the Guelph-born operatic tenor, former board chair of the Royal Conservatory of Music, and General Manager of the Metropolitan Opera (1935-1950), [[Edward Johnson (tenor)|Edward Johnson]].\n\n'''MacMillan Theatre''' \u2013 This 815-seat hall was designed for the production of operas and large ensemble concerts and named after former dean, [[Ernest MacMillan|Sir Ernest MacMillan]]. World-renowned for its excellent acoustics.\n\n'''Walter Hall''' \u2013 Commemorating [[Arnold Walter]], Director of the Faculty from 1952-1968, Walter Hall was designed for chamber concerts and recitals. The house seats 490. The hall also contains a two-manual tracker-action Casavant organ.\n\n'''Library''' \u2013 A part of the University of Toronto Library System, it is the largest music research collection in Canada. It contains over 300,000 printed materials, 180,000 recordings in the Sniderman Recordings Archive, 2,500 volumes in the Olnick Rare Book Room, and 3,500 titles in the Performance Collection.\n\n'''Electroacoustic Studio''' \u2013 The University of Toronto Electronic Music Studio opened in 1959. Originally located in a house on Division Street, it was moved to the Edward Johnson Building in 1963.\n\n==Degrees and programs==\n\n===Undergraduate studies===\n\n====Bachelor of Music in Performance (four-year program)====\nIn the classical stream, major instruments include those in the woodwind, brass and strings families, as well as percussion, piano, voice, guitar, harp, organ, accordion and historical instruments. In the jazz program, major instruments include double bass, guitar, percussion, piano, trumpet, trombone, saxophone and voice.\n\n====Bachelor of Music (four-year program)====\nOptions for major include: Comprehensive, Composition, History and Theory, Music Education, and Concurrent Teacher Education (five-year program in partnership with [[Ontario Institute for Studies in Education|OISE]]).\n\n====Advanced Certificate in Performance (one-year program)====\nThis is a one-year program of intensive full-time study, open to woodwinds, brass, percussion, strings, piano, voice and accordion. Students enrolling in this program have the option of specializing in Baroque music, utilizing period instruments in conjunction with Tafelmusik.\n\n====Artist Diploma (3-year program)====\nThis program is similar to the Bachelor of Music in Performance, but without academic-subject requirements. This is not open to students with a Bachelor of Music or a Bachelor of Music in Performance from the Faculty of Music.\n\n====Diploma in Operatic Performance (2- or 3-year program)====\nThree streams are available in this program \u2013 one for singers (2 or 3 years), one for operatic repetiteurs (2 years) and one for operatic stage directors (2 years).\n\n===Graduate studies===\n\n====Music performance and composition programs====\nPrograms include: MMus in Composition, in Music Technology and Digital Media, in Instrumental (solo piano, woodwinds, brass, percussion, strings), in Collaborative Piano, in Conducting, in Jazz Performance, in Opera, in Piano Pedagogy, in Voice and in Vocal Pedagogy; and DMA in Performance and in Composition.\n\n====Music program====\nPrograms include: MA and PhD in Music Education, Musicology, Theory, Performance and Ethnomusicology.\n\n==Performance Ensembles==\nIn addition to  large ensembles offered at the Faculty, there are various chamber music courses and collaborative piano courses. Most of these courses involve weekly masterclasses. There are also several world music ensemble courses offered, such as Japanese taiko drumming, African drumming and dancing, Latin-American percussion, Klezmer, tabla, Balinese Gamelan, Korean ensemble and steel pan.\n\n===Large ensembles===\n* University of Toronto Symphony Orchestra (UTSO) \u2013 conducted by Uri Mayer\n* University of Toronto Wind Ensemble \u2013 conducted by Dr. Gillian MacKay\n* University of Toronto Wind Symphony \u2013 conducted by Dr. Jeffrey Reynolds\n* University of Toronto MacMillan Singers \u2013 conducted by Dr. Hilary Apfelstadt\n* University of Toronto Women's Chorus \u2013 conducted by Frances Farrell\n* University of Toronto Women's Chamber Choir \u2013 conducted by Dr. Hilary Apfelstadt\n* University of Toronto Men's Chorus \u2013 conducted by Andr\u00e9-Louis Heywood\n* University of Toronto Jazz Orchestras \u2013 conducted by Jim Lewis and Gordon Foote\n* University of Toronto Vocal Jazz Ensemble \u2013 conducted by Christine Duncan\n* University of Toronto Guitar Orchestra - conducted by Jeffrey McFadden\n* Contemporary Music Ensemble (gamUT) \u2013 directed by Wallace Halladay\n* University of Toronto Percussion Ensemble \u2013 conducted by Beverley Johnston\n* Early Music Ensembles \u2013 conducted by Ivars Taurins\n* Schola Cantorum - conducted by [[Daniel Taylor (countertenor)|Daniel Taylor]]\n\n==Annual events==\n'''New Music Festival''' - Each year, the Faculty of Music hosts the University of Toronto New Music Festival at the end of January. The festival plays host to at least one distinguished guest in composition.\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Past deans===\n1918-1927 [[Augustus Stephen Vogt]]\n\n1927-1952 [[Ernest MacMillan|Sir Ernest MacMillan]]\n\n1952-1968 [[Arnold Walter]] (Director)\n\n1953-1970 [[Boyd Neel]] (Dean)\n\n1970-1977 [[John Beckwith (composer)|John Beckwith]]\n\n1977-1984 [[Gustav Ciamaga]]\n\n1984-1990 Carl Morey\n\n1990-1995 [[Paul Pedersen (composer)|Paul Pedersen]]\n\n1995-1996 Robert Falck (Acting Dean)\n\n1996-2004 David Beach\n\n2004-2007 Gage Averill\n\n2007-2010 Russell Hartenberger\n\n2011\u2013present Don McLean\n\n===Notable faculty (past and present)===\n* [[Jacques Abram]] - pianist\n* [[Robert Aitken (composer)|Robert Aitken]] - composer, flautist\n* [[Raffi Armenian]] - conductor, composer, pianist\n* [[John Beckwith (composer)|John Beckwith]] - composer, writer, broadcaster, pianist \n* [[Boris Berlin]] - pianist\n* [[Denis Brott]] - cellist\n* [[Walter Buczynski]] - composer, pianist\n* [[Chan Ka Nin]] - composer\n* [[Andrew Dawes]] - violinist\n* [[Lorand Fenyves]] - violinist\n* [[Harry Freedman]] - composer, English hornist\n* [[Hans Gruber (conductor)|Hans Gruber]] - conductor\n* [[Christos Hatzis]] - composer\n* [[John Hawkins (Canadian composer)|John Hawkins]] - composer, conductor\n* [[Pierre H\u00e9tu]] - conductor, pianist\n* [[Derek Holman]] - choral conductor, organist, composer\n* [[Sandra Horst]] - pianist, vocal coach, choral conductor\n* [[Jacques Israelievitch]] - violinist\n* [[Kelly Jefferson]] - jazz saxophonist\n* [[Richard Johnston (composer)|Richard Johnston]] - composer\n* [[Norbert Kraft]] - guitarist\n* [[Anton\u00edn Kub\u00e1lek]] - pianist\n* [[Gary Kulesha]] - composer\n* [[Larysa Kuzmenko]] - composer, pianist\n* [[Ettore Mazzoleni]] - conductor\n* [[John McKay (pianist)|John McKay]] - pianist\n* [[Albert Pratz]] - violinist, conductor, composer\n* [[Godfrey Ridout]] - composer, conductor\n* [[Eugene Rittich]] - horn\n* [[Shauna Rolston]] - cellist\n* [[Chase Sanborn]] - jazz trumpet\n* [[Ezra Schabas]]\n* [[Leo Smith (composer)|Leo Smith]] - composer\n* [[John Weinzweig]] - composer\n* [[Carol Welsman]] - jazz vocalist and pianist\n* [[S. Drummond Wolff]] - organist, choirmaster, composer\n* [[John Wyre]] - percussionist, composer\n* [[David Zafer]] - violinist\n\n===Notable alumni===\n====Composers====\n* [[Kristi Allik]]\n* [[Wayne Barlow]]\n* [[John Beckwith (composer)|John Beckwith]]\n* [[Norma Beecroft]]\n* [[Michael Bussiere]]\n* [[Brian Cherney]]\n* [[Gustav Ciamaga]]\n* [[F. R. C. Clarke]]\n* [[Mychael Danna]]\n* [[Omar Daniel]]\n* [[Samuel Dolin]]\n* [[Leila Fletcher]]\n* [[Clifford Ford]]\n* [[Srul Irving Glick]] - composer\n* [[David Grimes (composer)|David Grimes]]\n* [[Kelsey Jones]] - composer, pianist\n* [[Todor Kobakov]] - composer, pianist\n* [[Serouj Kradjian]] - composer, pianist\n* [[Veronika Krausas]]\n* [[Bruce Mather]] - composer, pianist\n* [[James Montgomery (composer)|James Montgomery]]\n* [[\u00c9ric Morin]]\n* [[Owen Pallett]] - composer, violinist\n* [[Donald Patriquin]] - composer, organist, choir conductor\n* [[Paul Pedersen (composer)|Paul Pedersen]]\n* [[Bob Pritchard (composer)|Bob Pritchard]]\n* [[Imant Raminsh]] - composer, violinist, conductor\n* [[John Rea (composer)|John Rea]]\n* [[James Rolfe]] - composer\n* [[Clark Ross]] - composer, guitarist\n* [[Terry Rusling]] - electronic composer\n* [[David Squires]]\n* [[Timothy Sullivan (composer)|Timothy Sullivan]] - Composer, music educator\n* [[Peter Tahourdin]]\n* Sandy Thorburn - composer, theatre director\n* [[Kevin Turcotte]] - trumpet player\n* [[John Weinzweig]]\n* [[Alfred Whitehead]] - composer, organist, choral conductor\n* [[Charles Wilson (composer)|Charles Wilson]] - composer, choral conductor\n* [[Chan Wing-wah]] - conductor, composer\n\n====Conductors====\n* Nathan Brock - conductor\n* Petar Dundjerski - flautist, conductor\n* [[Victor Feldbrill]] - conductor, violinist\n* [[James Gayfer]] - bandmaster, clarinettist, composer\n* [[Graham George]] - composer, organist, choirmaster\n* [[Elmer Iseler]] - choir conductor\n* [[Brian Jackson (conductor)|Brian Jackson]] - conductor\n* [[Janko Kastelic]] - conductor\n* [[Julian Kuerti]] - conductor\n* Richard Lee - violinist, conductor\n* [[Leon Major]] - opera and theatre director\n* Evan Mitchell - conductor\n* [[Glenn Price]] - conductor\n* Wayne Strongman - conductor, Founding Managing Artistic Director, Tapestry New Opera\n\n====Instrumentalists====\n* [[James Campbell (clarinetist)|James Campbell]] - clarinettist\n* [[David Bourque]] - clarinettist\n* [[Liona Boyd]] - guitarist\n* [[David Braid]] - jazz pianist, composer\n* [[Howard Brown (pianist)|Howard Brown]] - pianist\n* [[Jarred Dunn]] - pianist\n* [[David J. Elliott]] - trombonist, Professor of Music and Music Education, New York University\n* Mark Fewer - violinist; Associate Professor, Schulich School of Music, McGill University\n* [[Jonathan Freeman-Attwood]] - trumpet, Principal of the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London\n* Jeffrey McFadden - guitarist\n* Attila Fias - jazz pianist, composer, arranger, recording artist\n* Timothy Phelan - guitarist\n* [[Walter Prystawski]] - violinist\n* [[Erika Raum]] - violinist\n* [[Yaroslav Senyshyn]] - pianist; Professor, Simon Fraser University\n* [[Peter Elyakim Taussig]] - pianist, composer\n* [[Fergus McWilliam]] - horn player, with Berlin Philharmonic\n* Carolyn Gadiel Warner - violinist, pianist with the Cleveland Orchestra\n\n====Musicologists and others====\n* Gregory G. Butler - Professor Emeritus (musicology), University of British Columbia\n* [[Eric Chafe]] - Victor and Gwendolyn Beinfield Professor of Music, Brandeis University\n* Beverley Diamond - Canada Research Chair in Traditional Music, Ethnomusicology, Professor at Memorial University\n* [[Cliff Eisen]] - Associate Editor, New K\u00f6chel Catalogue, King's College London\n* [[Jonathan Freeman-Attwood]] - Principal, [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London\n* Helmut Kallmann - Canadian Music historian\n* [[Simon Morrison]] - Professor of Music, Princeton\n* [[Paolo Pietropaolo]] - music journalist and CBC Radio broadcaster\n* Alison Pybus - Vice-President, Vocal Division, IMG Artists, New York\n* Peter Simon - President, Royal Conservatory of Music\n\n====Vocalists====\n* [[Russell Braun]] - baritone\n* [[Measha Brueggergosman]] - soprano\n* [[Ariana Chris]] - mezzo-soprano\n* Sally Dibblee - soprano\n* John Fanning - baritone\n* [[Barbara Fris]] - soprano\n* [[Barbara Hannigan]] - soprano\n* Rosemarie Landry - soprano\n* Ermanno Mauro - tenor\n* Mary Morrison - soprano\n* [[Patricia O'Callaghan]] - soprano\n* Mark Pedrotti - baritone\n* [[Adrianne Pieczonka]] - soprano\n* [[Brett Polegato]] - baritone\n* [[David Pomeroy]] - tenor\n* [[Teresa Stratas]] - soprano\n* [[Jon Vickers]] - heldentenor\n\n==See also==\n* [[Music of Canada]]\n* [[Music of Ontario]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.music.utoronto.ca}}\n* [https://discoverarchives.library.utoronto.ca/index.php/otufm04-faculty-of-music Archival collection] at [https://music.library.utoronto.ca/ University of Toronto Music Library]\n\n{{Portal bar|Classical music|Jazz|Music|Canada}}\n\n[[Category:University of Toronto|Music]]\n[[Category:Music schools in Canada]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1844]]\n[[Category:1844 establishments in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name           = Faculty of Music\n| native_name    = \n| image_name     = \n| image_size     = \n| image_alt      = \n| caption        = \n| motto          = \n| motto_lang     = \n| motto_eng      = \n| former_names   = \n| established    = {{Start date|1918}}\n| closed         = \n| type           = [[Faculty (division)|Faculty]]\n| parent         = \n| affiliation    = [[University of Toronto]]\n| city           = [[Toronto]]\n| province       = [[Ontario]]\n| country        = [[Canada]]\n| coor           = {{coord|43.666717|N|79.394621|W|region:CA-ON_type:landmark_source:GoogleMaps|display=inline, title|format=dms}}\n| dean           = Don McLean\n| academic_staff = \n| administrative_staff = \n| students       = \n| undergrad      = \n| postgrad       = \n| doctoral       = \n| alumni         = \n| colours        = \n| symbol         = \n| website        = {{URL|www.music.utoronto.ca}}\n| logo           = [[File:University of Toronto Faculty of Music Black Logo.jpg|200px]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Faculty of Music at the University of Toronto''' is one of several professional faculties at the [[University of Toronto]]. The Faculty of Music is located at the Edward Johnson Building, just south of the [[Royal Ontario Museum]] and north of [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]], west of [[Museum (TTC)|Museum Subway Station]]. MacMillan Theatre and Walter Hall are located in the Edward Johnson Building. The Faculty of Music South building contains rehearsal rooms and offices, and the Upper Jazz Studio performance space is located at 90 Wellesley Street West. In 2011, the Faculty of Music hired Don McLean as the new Dean.\n\n==Historical timeline==\n\n*'''1844''' Music was considered a discipline worthy of recognition by the University of Toronto (named King's College until 1850) and examinations were held for candidates wishing to receive a degree in music.<ref name=Chandler>{{cite book|last=Chandler|first=Ron|title=Alumni Directory: Historical Introduction|year=1990|publisher=University of Toronto, Faculty of Music|location=Toronto|isbn=0-7727-8555-4|pages=4\u201335}}</ref>\n*'''1846''' James Paton Clarke became the first person in Canada to be awarded the degree of Bachelor of Music.<ref name=\"Canadian Encyclopedia\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=McMillan|first=Barclay|title=James Paton Clarke|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/james-paton-clarke|publisher=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|accessdate=6 December 2012}}</ref>\n*'''1858''' George Strathy received Canada's first D Mus at Trinity College.<ref name=Chandler /><ref name=\"Canadian Encyclopedia\">{{cite web|last=Green; Spier|first=J. Paul; Susan|title=Music at University of Toronto|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/emc/music-at-university-of-toronto|publisher=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=10 December 2012}}</ref>\n*'''1886''' [[The Royal Conservatory of Music|The Toronto Conservatory of Music]] was incorporated, and was operated in conjunction with the University of Toronto from its beginnings.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1904''' [[Trinity College, Toronto|Trinity College]] was relieved of the music degree, and the MusBac became a University of Toronto degree.<ref name=\"John Beckwith\">{{cite book|last=Beckwith|first=John|title=Music at Toronto: A Personal Account|year=1995|publisher=University of Toronto Press Incorporated|location=Toronto|isbn=0-9699416-0-9}}</ref>\n*'''1918''' The Faculty of Music was established. The Senate of the University withdrew its affiliations with various music schools ([[Toronto College of Music]] and [[Royal Hamilton College of Music]]) and inaugurated a Faculty of Music to teach music and administer examinations. Along with his duties as music director of the Toronto Conservatory, [[Augustus Stephen Vogt]] was appointed Dean.<ref name=Chandler /><ref name=\"Canadian Encyclopedia\" />\n*'''1921''' The Ontario Legislature passed Bill 154, an act that vested the assets of the Toronto Conservatory of Music in the University of Toronto.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1926''' [[Ernest MacMillan|Sir Ernest MacMillan]] became Dean of the Faculty of Music and Principal of the Toronto Conservatory of Music.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1934''' \u201cCourses of Instruction\u201d were introduced, the first courses to be taught at the Faculty.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1945''' [[Ettore Mazzoleni]] became Principal of the Conservatory. Edward Johnson was appointed to the Board of Governors of the University and the Conservatory.\n*'''1946''' [[Arnold Walter]] established and was appointed Director of the Senior School for advanced students at the Conservatory. He also established the three-year Artist Diploma program and the Opera School.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1947''' The Toronto Conservatory of Music received the Royal charter from [[George VI|King George VI]], and became The Royal Conservatory of Music.\n*'''1952-1953''' A new administrative structure was created \u2013 The Royal Conservatory of Music at the University of Toronto placed a Dean in charge of all music programs. There would be one Dean in charge of two divisions: The School of Music (the previous Royal Conservatory of Music) headed by a Principal (Ettore Mazzoleni) and the Faculty of Music, headed by a Director (Arnold Walter). The School of Music ran the opera school, examinations of grade 1 to ARCT, and the speech arts department. The Faculty of Music ran the Licentiate and Artist diploma courses, and the Senior School no longer existed. [[Boyd Neel]] was appointed Dean of the 'umbrella' RCMT.<ref name=Chandler /><ref name=\"Canadian Encyclopedia\" />\n*'''1954''' The first program for the Master of Music was introduced.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1958-1959''' The University's President's Report announced that the Faculty of Music would have a new building and the School of Music would move to McMaster Hall on Bloor Street.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1959''' Plans for an electronic music studio were announced, historically the second in a North American university.\n*'''1961-1962''' The MusBac became a four-year program.\n*'''1962''' The Faculty of Music moved to the newly built Edward Johnson Building (the first building in Canada designed specifically for professional music study), though the official opening was delayed until spring 1964, and the School of Music moved to McMaster Hall.\n*'''1966-1967''' The first Bachelor of Music in Performance was offered.\n*'''1969''' The Opera School transferred to the Faculty of Music and a two-year opera diploma program was approved.\n*'''1969-1970''' A new curriculum was put into place \u2013 \u2018basic music\u2019 subjects in the first two years were common to all students. The Master of Music in Performance was approved.\n*'''1970''' [[John Beckwith (composer)|John Beckwith]] was appointed Dean. The post of Director of the Faculty of Music was eliminated. The Faculty became responsibility of the Dean, and the School of Music was renamed to its more popular name, the Royal Conservatory of Music.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1973-1974''' This was the last year Conservatory performance certificates were accepted as alternatives for admission to the Faculty of Music. All incoming students were subsequently auditioned and interviewed.<ref name=\"John Beckwith\"/>\n*'''1977''' [[Gustav Ciamaga]] appointed Dean\n*'''1978-1979''' Theory and Conducting majors were added to the undergraduate curriculum. The conducting major was discontinued in 1986.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1979-1980''' The first jazz courses were offered.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1983-1984''' The University created the Committee on the Future of Music Studies to review how the faculty and conservatory were operated and organized. In 1984, its final report recommended the eventual separation of the Conservatory from the University.<ref name=Chandler />\n*'''1984''' Carl Morey appointed Dean.\n*'''1990''' [[Paul Pedersen (composer)|Paul Pedersen]] appointed Dean.\n*'''1991''' The Royal Conservatory of Music Act of the Ontario Legislature confirms the separation of the Conservatory from the University of Toronto and re-established The Royal Conservatory's status as a fully independent, not-for-profit entity. The MusBac in Jazz Performance is introduced.<ref name=\"Canadian Encyclopedia\" />\n*'''1996''' David Beach appointed Dean.\n*'''2004''' Gage Averill appointed Dean.\n*'''2007''' Russell Hartenberger was appointed Interim Dean and named Dean in 2008.\n*'''2007''' Concurrent Teacher's Education Program established, as well as the Doctorate in Musical Arts (DMA) in Performance.\n*'''2011''' Don McLean appointed Dean.\n\n==Research and collaborations==\n\n===Research institutes===\nThe Music and Health Research Collaboratory (MaHRC), established in 2012, is a collaborative group of researchers that aims to better understand the role of sound in human experiences, exploring connections of sound to the human experience of health.\n\nThe Institute for Canadian Music, established in 1984, aims to promote and support all areas of Canadian Music Study.\n\n===Artists in residence===\n* [[Canadian Brass]] - Distinguished Ensemble in Residence 2011-2015\n* Cecilia String Quartet - Ensemble in Residence\n* [[Gryphon Trio]] - Artists in Residence\n* [[Nexus (percussion ensemble)|Nexus]] - Resident Percussion Ensemble\n* [[Tafelmusik Baroque Orchestra|Tafelmusik]] - Baroque Orchestra in Residence\n* Young Voices Toronto (formerly High Park Choirs of Toronto) - Children's Choir in Residence\n* [[St. Lawrence String Quartet]] - Visiting Chamber Ensemble\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:EdwardJohnsonBuilding2.jpg|thumb|Edward Johnson Building]]\n'''Edward Johnson Building''' \u2013 Home of the Faculty of Music since 1962, the Edward Johnson Building houses many offices and classrooms, as well as two floors of practice rooms, two large rehearsal rooms, the Faculty of Music Library, the University of Toronto Electronic Music Studio (UTEMS), a theatre for large ensemble performances (MacMillan Theatre) and a smaller recital hall (Walter Hall), and named for the Guelph-born operatic tenor, former board chair of the Royal Conservatory of Music, and General Manager of the Metropolitan Opera (1935-1950), [[Edward Johnson (tenor)|Edward Johnson]].\n\n'''MacMillan Theatre''' \u2013 This 815-seat hall was designed for the production of operas and large ensemble concerts and named after former dean, [[Ernest MacMillan|Sir Ernest MacMillan]]. World-renowned for its excellent acoustics.\n\n'''Walter Hall''' \u2013 Commemorating [[Arnold Walter]], Director of the Faculty from 1952-1968, Walter Hall was designed for chamber concerts and recitals. The house seats 490. The hall also contains a two-manual tracker-action Casavant organ.\n\n'''Library''' \u2013 A part of the University of Toronto Library System, it is the largest music research collection in Canada. It contains over 300,000 printed materials, 180,000 recordings in the Sniderman Recordings Archive, 2,500 volumes in the Olnick Rare Book Room, and 3,500 titles in the Performance Collection.\n\n'''Electroacoustic Studio''' \u2013 The University of Toronto Electronic Music Studio opened in 1959. Originally located in a house on Division Street, it was moved to the Edward Johnson Building in 1963.\n\n==Degrees and programs==\n\n===Undergraduate studies===\n\n====Bachelor of Music in Performance (four-year program)====\nIn the classical stream, major instruments include those in the woodwind, brass and strings families, as well as percussion, piano, voice, guitar, harp, organ, accordion and historical instruments. In the jazz program, major instruments include double bass, guitar, percussion, piano, trumpet, trombone, saxophone and voice.\n\n====Bachelor of Music (four-year program)====\nOptions for major include: Comprehensive, Composition, History and Theory, Music Education, and Concurrent Teacher Education (five-year program in partnership with [[Ontario Institute for Studies in Education|OISE]]).\n\n====Advanced Certificate in Performance (one-year program)====\nThis is a one-year program of intensive full-time study, open to woodwinds, brass, percussion, strings, piano, voice and accordion. Students enrolling in this program have the option of specializing in Baroque music, utilizing period instruments in conjunction with Tafelmusik.\n\n====Artist Diploma (3-year program)====\nThis program is similar to the Bachelor of Music in Performance, but without academic-subject requirements. This is not open to students with a Bachelor of Music or a Bachelor of Music in Performance from the Faculty of Music.\n\n====Diploma in Operatic Performance (2- or 3-year program)====\nThree streams are available in this program \u2013 one for singers (2 or 3 years), one for operatic repetiteurs (2 years) and one for operatic stage directors (2 years).\n\n===Graduate studies===\n\n====Music performance and composition programs====\nPrograms include: MMus in Composition, in Music Technology and Digital Media, in Instrumental (solo piano, woodwinds, brass, percussion, strings), in Collaborative Piano, in Conducting, in Jazz Performance, in Opera, in Piano Pedagogy, in Voice and in Vocal Pedagogy; and DMA in Performance and in Composition.\n\n====Music program====\nPrograms include: MA and PhD in Music Education, Musicology, Theory, Performance and Ethnomusicology.\n\n==Performance Ensembles==\nIn addition to  large ensembles offered at the Faculty, there are various chamber music courses and collaborative piano courses. Most of these courses involve weekly masterclasses. There are also several world music ensemble courses offered, such as Japanese taiko drumming, African drumming and dancing, Latin-American percussion, Klezmer, tabla, Balinese Gamelan, Korean ensemble and steel pan.\n\n===Large ensembles===\n* University of Toronto Symphony Orchestra (UTSO) \u2013 conducted by Uri Mayer\n* University of Toronto Wind Ensemble \u2013 conducted by Dr. Gillian MacKay\n* University of Toronto Wind Symphony \u2013 conducted by Dr. Jeffrey Reynolds\n* University of Toronto MacMillan Singers \u2013 conducted by Dr. Hilary Apfelstadt\n* University of Toronto Women's Chorus \u2013 conducted by Frances Farrell\n* University of Toronto Women's Chamber Choir \u2013 conducted by Dr. Hilary Apfelstadt\n* University of Toronto Men's Chorus \u2013 conducted by Andr\u00e9-Louis Heywood\n* University of Toronto Jazz Orchestras \u2013 conducted by Jim Lewis and Gordon Foote\n* University of Toronto Vocal Jazz Ensemble \u2013 conducted by Christine Duncan\n* University of Toronto Guitar Orchestra - conducted by Jeffrey McFadden\n* Contemporary Music Ensemble (gamUT) \u2013 directed by Wallace Halladay\n* University of Toronto Percussion Ensemble \u2013 conducted by Beverley Johnston\n* Early Music Ensembles \u2013 conducted by Ivars Taurins\n* Schola Cantorum - conducted by [[Daniel Taylor (countertenor)|Daniel Taylor]]\n\n==Annual events==\n'''New Music Festival''' - Each year, the Faculty of Music hosts the University of Toronto New Music Festival at the end of January. The festival plays host to at least one distinguished guest in composition.\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Past deans===\n1918-1927 [[Augustus Stephen Vogt]]\n\n1927-1952 [[Ernest MacMillan|Sir Ernest MacMillan]]\n\n1952-1968 [[Arnold Walter]] (Director)\n\n1953-1970 [[Boyd Neel]] (Dean)\n\n1970-1977 [[John Beckwith (composer)|John Beckwith]]\n\n1977-1984 [[Gustav Ciamaga]]\n\n1984-1990 Carl Morey\n\n1990-1995 [[Paul Pedersen (composer)|Paul Pedersen]]\n\n1995-1996 Robert Falck (Acting Dean)\n\n1996-2004 David Beach\n\n2004-2007 Gage Averill\n\n2007-2010 Russell Hartenberger\n\n2011\u2013present Don McLean\n\n===Notable faculty (past and present)===\n* [[Jacques Abram]] - pianist\n* [[Robert Aitken (composer)|Robert Aitken]] - composer, flautist\n* [[Raffi Armenian]] - conductor, composer, pianist\n* [[John Beckwith (composer)|John Beckwith]] - composer, writer, broadcaster, pianist \n* [[Boris Berlin]] - pianist\n* [[Denis Brott]] - cellist\n* [[Walter Buczynski]] - composer, pianist\n* [[Chan Ka Nin]] - composer\n* [[Andrew Dawes]] - violinist\n* [[Lorand Fenyves]] - violinist\n* [[Harry Freedman]] - composer, English hornist\n* [[Hans Gruber (conductor)|Hans Gruber]] - conductor\n* [[Christos Hatzis]] - composer\n* [[John Hawkins (Canadian composer)|John Hawkins]] - composer, conductor\n* [[Pierre H\u00e9tu]] - conductor, pianist\n* [[Derek Holman]] - choral conductor, organist, composer\n* [[Sandra Horst]] - pianist, vocal coach, choral conductor\n* [[Jacques Israelievitch]] - violinist\n* [[Kelly Jefferson]] - jazz saxophonist\n* [[Richard Johnston (composer)|Richard Johnston]] - composer\n* [[Norbert Kraft]] - guitarist\n* [[Anton\u00edn Kub\u00e1lek]] - pianist\n* [[Gary Kulesha]] - composer\n* [[Larysa Kuzmenko]] - composer, pianist\n* [[Ettore Mazzoleni]] - conductor\n* [[John McKay (pianist)|John McKay]] - pianist\n* [[Albert Pratz]] - violinist, conductor, composer\n* [[Godfrey Ridout]] - composer, conductor\n* [[Eugene Rittich]] - horn\n* [[Shauna Rolston]] - cellist\n* [[Chase Sanborn]] - jazz trumpet\n* [[Ezra Schabas]]\n* [[Leo Smith (composer)|Leo Smith]] - composer\n* [[John Weinzweig]] - composer\n* [[Carol Welsman]] - jazz vocalist and pianist\n* [[S. Drummond Wolff]] - organist, choirmaster, composer\n* [[John Wyre]] - percussionist, composer\n* [[David Zafer]] - violinist\n\n===Notable alumni===\n====Composers====\n* [[Kristi Allik]]\n* [[Wayne Barlow]]\n* [[John Beckwith (composer)|John Beckwith]]\n* [[Norma Beecroft]]\n* [[Michael Bussiere]]\n* [[Brian Cherney]]\n* [[Gustav Ciamaga]]\n* [[F. R. C. Clarke]]\n* [[Mychael Danna]]\n* [[Omar Daniel]]\n* [[Samuel Dolin]]\n* [[Leila Fletcher]]\n* [[Clifford Ford]]\n* [[Srul Irving Glick]] - composer\n* [[David Grimes (composer)|David Grimes]]\n* [[Kelsey Jones]] - composer, pianist\n* [[Todor Kobakov]] - composer, pianist\n* [[Serouj Kradjian]] - composer, pianist\n* [[Veronika Krausas]]\n* [[Bruce Mather]] - composer, pianist\n* [[James Montgomery (composer)|James Montgomery]]\n* [[\u00c9ric Morin]]\n* [[Owen Pallett]] - composer, violinist\n* [[Donald Patriquin]] - composer, organist, choir conductor\n* [[Paul Pedersen (composer)|Paul Pedersen]]\n* [[Bob Pritchard (composer)|Bob Pritchard]]\n* [[Imant Raminsh]] - composer, violinist, conductor\n* [[John Rea (composer)|John Rea]]\n* [[James Rolfe]] - composer\n* [[Clark Ross]] - composer, guitarist\n* [[Terry Rusling]] - electronic composer\n* [[David Squires]]\n* [[Timothy Sullivan (composer)|Timothy Sullivan]] - Composer, music educator\n* [[Peter Tahourdin]]\n* Sandy Thorburn - composer, theatre director\n* [[Kevin Turcotte]] - trumpet player\n* [[John Weinzweig]]\n* [[Alfred Whitehead]] - composer, organist, choral conductor\n* [[Charles Wilson (composer)|Charles Wilson]] - composer, choral conductor\n* [[Chan Wing-wah]] - conductor, composer\n\n====Conductors====\n* Nathan Brock - conductor\n* Petar Dundjerski - flautist, conductor\n* [[Victor Feldbrill]] - conductor, violinist\n* [[James Gayfer]] - bandmaster, clarinettist, composer\n* [[Graham George]] - composer, organist, choirmaster\n* [[Elmer Iseler]] - choir conductor\n* [[Brian Jackson (conductor)|Brian Jackson]] - conductor\n* [[Janko Kastelic]] - conductor\n* [[Julian Kuerti]] - conductor\n* Richard Lee - violinist, conductor\n* [[Leon Major]] - opera and theatre director\n* Evan Mitchell - conductor\n* [[Glenn Price]] - conductor\n* Wayne Strongman - conductor, Founding Managing Artistic Director, Tapestry New Opera\n\n====Instrumentalists====\n* [[James Campbell (clarinetist)|James Campbell]] - clarinettist\n* [[David Bourque]] - clarinettist\n* [[Liona Boyd]] - guitarist\n* [[David Braid]] - jazz pianist, composer\n* [[Howard Brown (pianist)|Howard Brown]] - pianist\n* [[Jarred Dunn]] - pianist\n* [[David J. Elliott]] - trombonist, Professor of Music and Music Education, New York University\n* Mark Fewer - violinist; Associate Professor, Schulich School of Music, McGill University\n* [[Jonathan Freeman-Attwood]] - trumpet, Principal of the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London\n* Jeffrey McFadden - guitarist\n* Attila Fias - jazz pianist, composer, arranger, recording artist\n* Timothy Phelan - guitarist\n* [[Walter Prystawski]] - violinist\n* [[Erika Raum]] - violinist\n* [[Yaroslav Senyshyn]] - pianist; Professor, Simon Fraser University\n* [[Peter Elyakim Taussig]] - pianist, composer\n* [[Fergus McWilliam]] - horn player, with Berlin Philharmonic\n* Carolyn Gadiel Warner - violinist, pianist with the Cleveland Orchestra\n\n====Musicologists and others====\n* Gregory G. Butler - Professor Emeritus (musicology), University of British Columbia\n* [[Eric Chafe]] - Victor and Gwendolyn Beinfield Professor of Music, Brandeis University\n* Beverley Diamond - Canada Research Chair in Traditional Music, Ethnomusicology, Professor at Memorial University\n* [[Cliff Eisen]] - Associate Editor, New K\u00f6chel Catalogue, King's College London\n* [[Jonathan Freeman-Attwood]] - Principal, [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London\n* Helmut Kallmann - Canadian Music historian\n* [[Simon Morrison]] - Professor of Music, Princeton\n* [[Paolo Pietropaolo]] - music journalist and CBC Radio broadcaster\n* Alison Pybus - Vice-President, Vocal Division, IMG Artists, New York\n* Peter Simon - President, Royal Conservatory of Music\n\n====Vocalists====\n* [[Russell Braun]] - baritone\n* [[Measha Brueggergosman]] - soprano\n* [[Ariana Chris]] - mezzo-soprano\n* Sally Dibblee - soprano\n* John Fanning - baritone\n* [[Barbara Fris]] - soprano\n* [[Barbara Hannigan]] - soprano\n* Rosemarie Landry - soprano\n* Ermanno Mauro - tenor\n* Mary Morrison - soprano\n* [[Patricia O'Callaghan]] - soprano\n* Mark Pedrotti - baritone\n* [[Adrianne Pieczonka]] - soprano\n* [[Brett Polegato]] - baritone\n* [[David Pomeroy]] - tenor\n* [[Teresa Stratas]] - soprano\n* [[Jon Vickers]] - heldentenor\n\n==See also==\n* [[Music of Canada]]\n* [[Music of Ontario]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.music.utoronto.ca}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Classical music|Jazz|Music|Canada}}\n\n[[Category:University of Toronto|Music]]\n[[Category:Music schools in Canada]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1844]]\n[[Category:1844 establishments in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Ra.shaw21", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Toronto_Faculty_of_Music"}
{"title_page": "Giant Step", "text_new": "{{for|the album by the musician Taj Mahal|Giant Step/De Ole Folks at Home}}\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name = Giant Step\n| image = [[File:Giant Step logo.png]]\n| image_bg = \n| parent = \n| founded = 1990\n| founder = Maurice Bernstein, \nJonathan Rudnick (1990-2001)\n| status = Active\n| distributor = \n| country = {{Flag|USA}}\n| location = [[New York City]], [[Los Angeles]]\n| url = http://www.giantstep.net/\n}}\n\n'''Giant Step''' is a media, events and marketing company headquartered in [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"facebook about\">{{cite web|title=Giant Step About|url=https://www.facebook.com/giantstep/info|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>   The company formerly released music through its [[record label]], Giant Step Records.<ref name=\"Jazz Times\">{{cite web|last=Terrell|first=Tom|title=Label Watch: Giant Step|url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/24721-label-watch-giant-step|publisher=Jazz Times|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=December 1997}}</ref> Giant Step is divided into two entities - the Giant Step brand, which promotes music and the creative agency, Giant Step Marketing, which provides marketing services to consumer brands.<ref name=linkedin>{{cite web|title=Giant Step Service|url=http://www.linkedin.com/company/giant-step/products?trk=top_nav_products|publisher=linkedin|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== The Groove Academy and early years ===\nGroove Academy began in 1990 as a party in [[New York City]].  The party was a weekly production of [[British people|British]] promoter, Maurice Bernstein, and his South African partner, Jonathan Rudnick.<ref name=grooveacademy>{{cite web|title=Groove Academy|url=http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/groove-academy|publisher=Giant Step|accessdate=20 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220060930/http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/groove-academy/|archive-date=20 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=Standard>{{cite web|title=A New York Tale: Giant Step|url=http://www.standardculture.com/posts/7804-A-New-York-Tale-Giant-Step|publisher=The Standard Culture|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=1 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131108234137/http://www.standardculture.com/posts/7804-A-New-York-Tale-Giant-Step|archive-date=8 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Initially unable to secure a loan from the bank, the pair borrowed money and used it to book acts and venues.<ref name=Winehouse/>  \u201cThe stars of the 70\u2019s, although they were highly sampled, were not getting recognition and were not being presented in a live forum,\u201d recalls Rudnick.<ref name=\"Jazz Times\" /> The two called their events, Groove Academy with its slogan, \u201cDedicated to the preservation of Funk.\u201d<ref>Mead, Rebecca, \"The Brit Pack,\" ''New York Magazine''. August 26, 1991, p. 111</ref><ref name=BritPack>{{cite journal|last=Mead|first=Rebecca|title=The Brit Pack|journal=New York Magazine|date=26 August 1991|pages=111}}</ref>\n\nBernstein recalled, \u201cThe first Groove Academy shows were put on by literally looking up artists in the [[telephone book]] \u2026 None of them had [[Music Booking Agent|agents]] then, we\u2019d just call them up at home and say \u2018are you interested in doing a show with us?\u2019[[Giant Step#cite%20note-DJ%20History-38|<sup>[38]</sup>]] The two called their events Groove Academy with its slogan, \u201cDedicated to the preservation of Funk\u201d and began rediscovering musicians whose records they had collected as teenagers. <sup>[10][[Giant Step#cite%20note-9|[9]]][[Giant Step#cite%20note-BritPack-10|[10]]]</sup>\n\nThe events were extended onto the dance floor under the new name Giant Step, after the fabled [[John Coltrane]] album ''[[Giant Steps]]''.<ref name=\"Winehouse\">{{cite web|last=Furman|first=Phyllis|title=Tribeca promoter's business creates buzz; helps launch Amy Winehouse |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/2.1353/tribeca-promoter-business-creates-buzz-helps-launch-amy-winehouse-article-1.285069|publisher=Daily News|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=2 March 2008}}</ref> The Giant Step party differentiated itself from Groove Academy with its emphasis on mixing [[Jazz]] and [[Hip Hop]]. Giant Step would soon go on tour around the States, [[Europe]] and [[Japan]].<ref name=\"djhistory\">{{cite web|title=Giant Step Company|url=http://www.djhistory.com/features/giant-step-1996|publisher=DJ History|accessdate=20 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109021634/http://www.djhistory.com/features/giant-step-1996|archive-date=9 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Giant Step party (1990s to early 2000s) ===\nThe Giant Step party started off as a weekly event that mixed live [[jazz]] and [[hiphop]]. While The Groove Academy staged concerts with [[Maceo Parker]], [[Isaac hayes|Isaac Hayes]], [[The Ohio Players]] and [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]],[[Giant Step#cite%20note-DJ%20History-38|<sup>[38]</sup>]] Bernstein and Rudnick extended onto the dancefloor with their Giant Step party. Greatly influenced by the [[acid jazz]] club-nights in [[England]], like [[Gilles Peterson|Gilles Peterson\u2019s]] [[Talkin' Loud|Talkin' Loud And Sayin' Something]],.[[Giant Step#cite%20note-DJ%20History-38|<sup>[38]</sup>]][[Giant Step#cite%20note-Acid%20Jazz%20Defines%20Cool-39|<sup>[39]</sup>]] Giant Step offered a stage where visiting [[rappers]] and jazz musicians, along with the regular Giant Step band, improvised to prerecorded [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]] and funk.[[Giant Step#cite%20note-40|<sup>[40]</sup>]] Giant Step hold as emerging acid jazz artists, like the [[Digable Planets]], [[The Brand New Heavies]] and [[Jamiroquai]], launched their stateside careers here.[[Giant Step#cite%20note-41|<sup>[41]</sup>]] Many other notable artists debuted at Giant Step shows as well including [[The Fugees]] and [[Massive Attack]].[[Giant Step#cite%20note-cielo-42|<sup>[42]</sup>]] The party originally took place at S.O.B.\u2019s but later moved to other venues such as Metropolis Caf\u00e9, Supper Club, Shine, New Music Caf\u00e9 and [[the Village Gate]].[[Giant Step#cite%20note-throwback-43|<sup>[43]</sup>]] In 2002 the weekly party was discontinued. Later the Giant Step party would be re-launched at the [[Hudson Hotel]]. Giant Step\u2019s events expanded into select markets outside of New York City, including shows in Los Angeles, [[Miami]], [[Chicago]] and [[Washington DC]].[[Giant Step#cite%20note-gsevents-37|<sup>[37]</sup>]] \n\n=== Record label ===\nAs the events continued to expand in the mid 90s, Giant Step moved into management, signing Dana Bryant, [[Repercussions (band)]], and [[Groove Collective]], securing record deals for the three on [[Warner Brothers]].<ref name=\"Jazz Times\"/> Other artists managed include [[Raw Stylus]], whom Giant Step signed to [[Geffen Records]].<ref name=Standard/> During this time Giant Step worked with [[Gary Katz]], best known for his work with [[Steely Dan]], to help produce the albums for [[Groove Collective]], [[Repercussions (band)]] and [[Raw Stylus]].<ref name=trouserpress>{{cite web|title=Groove Collective: Gary Katz|url=http://www.trouserpress.com/entry.php?a=groove_collective|publisher=Trouser Press|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>    In 1995, record producer Tommy Lipuma took over [[GRP Records]] at [[MCA Records]] and invited Giant Step to set up there as an imprint label.  The first act to be signed to the label was the jazz group, [[Groove Collective]].<ref name=Standard/>\n\nIn early 1997, Giant Step achieved acclaim for their work with ''[[Nuyorican Soul]]'' and a partnership with [[Gilles Peterson]]\u2019s label, Talkin Loud.<ref name=discogs>{{cite web|title=Nuyorican Soul|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/2267-Nuyorican-Soul|publisher=Discogs|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>   The group was a collaboration between Latin house DJs, [[Little Louie Vega|\u201cLittle\u201d Louie Vega]] and [[Kenny \"Dope\" Gonzalez|Kenny \u201cDope\u201d Gonzales]], who were also commonly known as [[Masters at Work]].  Nuyorican Soul featured many real musicians as opposed to sampled or synthesized sounds. Musicians who took part in the project included [[George Benson]], [[Tito Puente]], [[Roy Ayers]], [[DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince|Jazzy Jeff]], [[Jocelyn Brown]], and salsa queen, India.<ref name=LATimes>{{cite web|last=Ali|first=Lorraine|title=Soul Men, 'Nuyorican' Style|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/jul/27/entertainment/ca-16575|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=27 July 1997}}</ref> Three singles from the first Nuyorican Soul album made it to the top of the [[Billboard Hot 100|Billboard Charts;]] \u201c[[Runaway (Nuyorican Soul song)|Runaway]]\u201d, \u201cYou Can Do It (Baby)\u201d and \u201cI Am The Black Gold Of The Sun.\u201d<ref name=\"Jazz Times\"/> The album, released in March 2007, sold over 50,000 units by the end of July the same year.<ref name=LATimes/> [[Epic Records]] soon approached Bernstein and Rudnick with an offer.<ref name=Standard/>  Although Giant Step was a music label, [[Epic Records]] was primarily interested in Giant Step\u2019s marketing capabilities and offered the company a retainer contract where their record label was a secondary priority.<ref name=Standard/>\n\n=== Music marketing and label discontinuation ===\nFor their first project with [[Epic Records]], Giant Step helped launch the career of [[Macy Gray]], followed by [[Jill Scott]] and the re-launch of [[Sade (band)|Sade]].<ref name=Standard/> The company promoted [[Macy Gray]] by getting her music played in caf\u00e9s, clubs, and restaurants. According to Rose Noone, VP of [[A&R]] at [[Epic Records]], the music was \u201cheard everywhere.\u201d<ref name=Standard/>   Giant Step went on to help [[Def Jam Records]] artist [[Musiq Soulchild]] by pushing his music in untapped markets.<ref name=RecordBreakers/>  The previously unknown singer sold 55,000 copies of his debut album in its first week.<ref name=RecordBreakers>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Ethan|title=Music: Record Breakers|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/music/features/4200/|publisher=New York Magazine|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nAlthough, Giant Step Records released a [[Gilles Peterson]] compilation with [[Epic Records]], Bernstein and Rudnick eventually grew frustrated with having an [[Imprint label|imprint deal]].<ref name=Standard/>  Corporate management denied their requests to sign artists like [[India Arie]] and Donnie, and so in 2000, Giant Step decided to start their own label.<ref name=Winehouse/> However the following year,  Rudnick would leave company to pursue other interests.<ref name=Winehouse/> With money received from Epic, Bernstein started work on a series of tracks with singer, Donnie, that would eventually become the album, ''Welcome to the Colored Section''.  Steve \u201cThe Scotman\u201d Harvey was enlisted as the [[Music producer|producer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Colored Section|url=http://stevethescotsmanharvey.bandcamp.com/album/the-colored-section|publisher=Steve The Scotsman Harvey|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref> Singles from this album include, \u201cDo You Know\u201d and \u201cCloud9\u201d.<ref name=donnie/>  ''Welcome to the Colored Section'' was called \u201cthe best soul record since Stevie Wonder's masterpieces of the 1970s,\" by the ''Boston Globe''.<ref name=donnie>{{cite web|title=Donnie|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/donnie-1|publisher=Answers.com|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>   The independent success of ''Welcome to the Colored Section'', brought a joint venture with [[Motown Records]] and private investment into the label.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cannick|first=Jasmyne|title=Donnie on Life After Motown and The Colored Section, the New Album, and His Newfound Freedom|url=http://jasmynecannick.typepad.com/jasmynecannickcom/2007/07/the-daily-news-.html|publisher=Jasmyne Cannick|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=July 2007}}</ref> Giant Step has also released albums for [[Carl Hancock]], [[Gilles Peterson]], Turntables on the Hudson, [[Ultra Nate]], [[Zero 7]], [[Jody Watley]], Donnie, Sara Devine, [[Jiva]] and [[Zap Mama]].<ref name=\"GiantStep\">{{cite web|url=http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/events/|title=Giant Step Events|publisher=Giant Step|accessdate=8 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206123332/http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/events/|archive-date=6 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHowever the venture had many operating issues.  Its financial troubles threatened Giant Step\u2019s marketing business and the company nearly shut down. After an expected second round of investment didn't come through, the label ground to a halt in 2005.<ref name=Winehouse/> With the record label closed, Giant Step focused its efforts on developing their marketing business.<ref name=Standard/>  Giant Step soon entered a collaboration with [[Sade (singer)|Sade]], and helped the artist sell 400,000 copies of her album during its first week in stores.<ref name=RecordBreakers/> In 2006, Universal Republic Records hired Giant Step to promote then-unknown [[Amy Winehouse]] - the company's grassroots campaign was acknowledge for supporting Winehouse's cross over into the mainstream in 2007.<ref name=\"Winehouse\" /> Other notable artists that were launched through Giant Step's music marketing program include [[Lady Gaga]], [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]] and [[Adele]].<ref name=GSM>{{cite web|title=Giant Step Marketing|url=http://www.giantstepmarketing.net/}}</ref>\n\n== Creative agency era ==\n\n=== 2000s ===\nAfter an initial foray with [[Levi's]] Miles Ahead Music Series and [[LG]], Giant Step expanded into [[brand marketing]] with their [[creative agency]], Giant Step Marketing.<ref name=\"RecordBreakers\" /> The company\u2019s work with the [[Levi\u2019s]] Miles Ahead Series debuted [[Jill Scott]], [[Air (French band)|Air]] and [[Massive Attack]].<ref name=\"RecordBreakers\" /> The series also featured bands such as [[Femi Kuti]], [[Kruder & Dorfmeister]], [[Fatboy Slim]], [[Morcheeba]], [[Bebel Gilberto]] and [[Terry Callier]].  For [[LG]], the agency coordinated press outreach, online promotions, and venues to help launch [[LG]]\u2019s new mobile phone line.  Events included performances by [[Jurassic 5]], [[Thievery Corporation]], [[The Pharcyde]], [[Zero 7]], [[Van Hunt]], [[Miss Kittin]], [[Raphael Saadiq]] and [[Everything But The Girl]].<ref name=\"Siegel\">{{cite web|title=GIANT STEP - LG MOBILE PHONES|url=http://lyndsaysiegel.com/project.php?currentpage=7|publisher=Lyndsay Siegel|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2007 and 2011 Giant Step Marketing produced music events for [[Ian Schrager]]'s [[Morgans Hotel Group]].<ref name=\"GiantStep\" /> This series included two years of [[Grammy]] and [[Fashion week]] events and featured artists such as [[The Roots]], [[Common (artist)|Common]], [[Grace Jones]], [[Erykah Badu]], [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]], [[Estelle (musician)|Estelle]], [[De La Soul]] and [[The Kills]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Morgans Hotel Group Announces New Music Series With Giant Step at Hudson in 2008: 'Monday Nights at Hudson'|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=194863&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1110492&highlight=|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131108225354/http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=194863&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1110492&highlight=|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-11-08|publisher=Corporate IR}}</ref>  In 2009, [[Svedka]] was brought in as a sponsor and the programs were expanded into the Svedka Future Music Series.<ref name=\"svedka\">{{cite web|title=Svedka Future Music Series|url=http://92bpm.com/2009/11/svedka-vodka-soda-with-twist-of-future.html|publisher=92BPM|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>  Notable musicians featured in the series include [[Robyn]], [[Wale (rapper)|Wale]], [[Mark Ronson]], [[N.E.R.D.]], [[Fitz & the Tantrums]], [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]] and [[Daft Punk]].<ref name=\"Svedka\">{{cite web|title=Svedka Vodka Giant Step|url=http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/svedka-vodka/|publisher=Giant Step|accessdate=8 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109005739/http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/svedka-vodka/|archive-date=9 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2008-2011 Giant Step Marketing launched [[Steve Madden (company)|Steve Madden]] Music.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Madden Music|url=http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/steve-madden-music/|access-date=2013-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109012510/http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/steve-madden-music/|archive-date=2013-11-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> The company created branded content, executed [[social media]] and online [[publicity]] campaigns and produced an experiential marketing program that aligned the brand with artists such as [[Katy Perry]], [[Lady Gaga]], K\u2019Naan, [[Katy B]] and [[Melanie Fiona]].<ref name=\"Madden\">{{cite web|title=Steve Madden Music Summer Series Continues with FreeSol at Le Bain, 8/15|url=http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/2011/08/steve-madden-music-summer-series-continues-with-freesol-at-le-bain-815/|publisher=Giant Step|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=9 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109005742/http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/2011/08/steve-madden-music-summer-series-continues-with-freesol-at-le-bain-815/|archive-date=9 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable campaigns (2011 and beyond) ===\nIn 2011, Giant Step worked with music producer [[David Guetta]] to create awareness for [[The Coca-Cola Company|Coca-Cola]]\u2019s energy drink, Burn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vimeo.com/61142143|title=David Guetta, Nothing But The Beat|publisher=Giant Step Marketing|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref> Later in 2011 Giant Step Marketing promoted the launch of [[Barneys New York]]\u2019s \u201cGaga\u2019s Workshop,\u201d a holiday collaboration with [[Lady Gaga]]. The company provided [[Public relations|PR]], [[social media]], digital and experiential campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swpnyc.com/2013/10/barneys-and-lady-gagas-workshop/|title=Gaga's Workshop}}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Giant Step Marketing launched Absolut X for [[Absolut Vodka]], a multi-year, integrated marketing program aimed at pairing music, art, & cocktails together.<ref name=\"absolutabout\">{{cite web|title=About Absolut X|url=http://absolutx.com/about|publisher=Absolut Vodka|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>  The program included 6 events in major markets in the form of a [[masquerade ball]], content, traditional advertising and a digital campaign.<ref name=\"absolutevents\">{{cite web|title=Absolut X Events|url=http://absolutx.com/events/|publisher=Absolut Vodka|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref> The experiential program won a gold Ex Award in 2013 (\"Best Production of An Event\") and garnered media coverage from national media outlets.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE BEST OF THE BEST IN 2013|url=http://emsummit.eventmarketer.com/exawards/|publisher=Event Marketing Summit|access-date=2013-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131123054958/http://emsummit.eventmarketer.com/exawards/|archive-date=2013-11-23|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Block|first=Tracy|title=Absolut X Blends Cocktails, Art, and Music at Miami Masquerade Tour Stop |url=http://www.bizbash.com/absolut-x-blends-cocktails-art-and-music-at-miami-masquerade-tour-stop/miami/story/26188/#sthash.JEEWjcg4.dpbs|publisher=BizBash|date=30 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nGiant Step Marketing produced and promoted the \"Music Experiment 2.0\" concert series in 2013 for [[Intel]] and [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]. The series featured artists such as [[Arcade Fire]], [[Empire of the Sun (band)|Empire of the Sun]] and [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]] and was broadcast on MTV Iggy and via livestream; the Arcade Fire show was also broadcast on \"[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]\" in partnership with ABC.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music Experiment 2.0|url=http://www.residentadvisor.net/event.aspx?504580}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theknow.denverpost.com/2013/10/30/watch-arcade-fire-on-jimmy-kimmel/80071/|title=Watch: Arcade Fire on Jimmy Kimmel, performing on the Capitol Records building|date=2013-10-30|website=The Know|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2013/10/arcade-fire-capitol-records-reflektor-kimmel/|title=See Arcade Fire Preach Outside the Capitol Records Building for \u2018Kimmel\u2019|date=2013-10-30|website=Spin|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The Intel series was later recognized with a silver [[Clio Awards|Clio Award]] in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clios.com/awards/winner/clio-music-integrated-campaign/intel-presents-the-music-experiment-powered-by-mtv-3336|title=- Intel Presents The Music Experiment, Powered by MTV Iggy|website=Clios|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Giant Step Marketing worked with [[Western Union]] to create a viral holiday campaign that would surprise real customers. The stunt was staged and filmed in Western Union\u2019s Times Square location, where customers were called in under the guise of \u201cbusiness,\u201d only to be greeted with a custom tent, decorated with family and country mementos, and their favorite home cooked meal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/steveolenski/2014/12/12/western-union-cooks-up-memories-for-the-holidays/|title=Western Union Cooks Up Memories For The Holidays|last=Olenski|first=Steve|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The campaign was credited for aiding in the \u201c[skyrocketing] of social engagement at Western Union,\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/western-union-karen-obrien/|title=How Social Engagement Skyrocketed at Western Union|last=Cohen{{!}}April 27|first=David|last2=2016 .aw-st0{fill:#F7EC13}.aw-st1{clip-path:url}.aw-st2{clip-path:url;fill:#020100}|website=adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> and recognized with a [[Shorty Awards|Shorty Award]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shortyawards.com/7th/wuhomecooked|title=#WUHomeCooked - The Shorty Awards|website=shortyawards.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nBernstein was tapped by [[Samsung Electronics|Samsung Electronics America]] in 2015 to serve as interim General Manager of its planned flagship experience center, and to oversee the opening of the building. Bernstein and Giant Step Marketing operated as Samsung\u2019s in-house agency, with the sole focus of launching Samsung 837 in 2016.<ref name=\"Swant{{!}}December 13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/agencies/new-york-shop-takes-jazz-approach-marketing-and-events-175020/|title=This New York Shop Takes a Jazz-like Approach to Marketing and Events|last=Swant{{!}}December 13|first=Marty|last2=2016 .aw-st0{fill:#F7EC13}.aw-st1{clip-path:url}.aw-st2{clip-path:url;fill:#020100}|website=adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://it-list.eventmarketer.com/?q=winner-158|title=Event Marketer - GIANT STEP:GIANT STEP|website=It List 2019|language=en-us|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> A first of its kind building in the heart of the Meatpacking District in Manhattan, Samsung 837 is home to concerts, cultural events, screenings and immersive experiences.<ref name=\"Warren\">{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2016/02/20/samsung-837-flagship/|title=Inside Samsung 837: Samsung's first North American flagship|last=Warren|first=Christina|website=Mashable|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The building, which has been recognized as a forerunner in the [[experiential retail]] category and was awarded \u201cBest Store Design of the Year,\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.designretailonline.com/news/awards-events/samsung-837-wins-best-store-design-of-the-year/|title=Samsung 837 wins Best Store Design of the Year|website=design:retail|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> showcases Samsung\u2019s technology in all of its programming.<ref name=\"Warren\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Giant Step Marketing was engaged by [[W Hotels]] and [[Marriott International]] to develop an integrated music platform, which eventually became W Records, the world\u2019s first-ever hotel music label.<ref name=\"Wang\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jennawang/2018/10/09/w-hotels-launches-first-ever-hotel-music-label/|title=W Hotels Launches First-Ever Hotel Music Label|last=Wang|first=Jenna|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref name=\"Wang\"/> In its first year, W Records signed and released new music from artists such as Amber Mark, [[Perfume Genius]], Roosevelt and [[Japanese Breakfast]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.marriott.com/2019/04/mic-drop-w-records-announces-japanese-breakfast-final-artist-in-the-programs-inaugural-class/|title=Mic Drop: W Records Announces Japanese Breakfast, Final Artist in the Program\u2019s Inaugural Class|date=2019-04-26|website=Marriott News Center|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> In September 2019, Giant Step was recognized with a bronze [[Clio Awards|Clio Award]] for W Records, in the \u201cIntegrated Campaign\u201d category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clios.com/music/winner/integrated-campaign/w-hotels/w-records-61267|title=W Hotels - W Records|website=Clios|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to its integrated campaign work, Giant Step Marketing is frequently hired to produce high-profile concerts for consumer brands in various global markets, including the opening of the Times Square EDITION Hotel with [[Diana Ross]] and [[Nile Rodgers]], the launch of [[SoundCloud]] Go with [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Spotify|Spotify\u2019s]] Latin Grammy Awards party with [[J Balvin]], [[Daddy Yankee]] and [[Luis Fonsi]], and [[Lincoln Motor Company]]\u2019s concert series featuring [[Gary Clark Jr.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|title=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref name=\"Swant{{!}}December 13\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8039180/buchanans-spotify-latin-grammy-nominees-performances|title=Buchanan's and Spotify Celebrate Latin Grammy Nominees With Performances by Sebastian Yatra, Luis Fonsi, Vives and More|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7685076/gary-clark-jr-lincoln-motor-company-ad-grammys-cord-video|title=Gary Clark Jr. Teams With Lincoln Motor Company for New TV Spot 'Cord': Exclusive|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Giant Step Marketing has been named in ''Event Marketer''\u2019s annual \u201cIt List\u201d of the world\u2019s top 100 event agencies every year since 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/list/2014itlist/|title=2014 It List Archives - Event Marketer|website=eventmarketer.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/article/2015-list-check-industrys-top-100-event-agencies/|title=The 2015 It List is Here... Top 100 Event Agencies - Event Marketer|website=eventmarketer.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/2016-it-list/|title=The 2016 It List - Event Marketer|website=eventmarketer.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2017/|title=Event Marketer - The 2017 It List|website=2017 It List|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|title=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/article/the-2019-it-list/|title=The 2019 It List: Recognizing the Top 100 Event Agencies|website=eventmarketer.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>   \n\n=== Creative agency clients (past and present) ===\n[[Absolut Vodka|Absolut]] ([[Pernod Ricard]]), [[Adidas]], [[Bacardi]], [[Barneys New York]], [[Coca-Cola]], Clarks, EDITION Hotels, [[HBO]], [[HP Inc.]], [[Intel]], [[Levi Strauss & Co.|Levi's]], [[LG Corporation]], [[Marriott International]], [[Morgans Hotel Group]], [[MTV]] ([[Viacom International Media Networks|Viacom]]), [[Old Navy]], [[SoundCloud]], [[Spotify]], [[Sundance TV]], [[Lincoln Motor Company|The Lincoln Motor Company]], [[Red Bull]], [[Steve Madden (company)|Steve Madden]], [[Western Union]], [[W Hotels]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.giantstep.net|title=Giant Step client list|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Thought leadership ===\nBernstein joined the faculty at [[New York University Tisch School of the Arts]] in 2018, teaching music and entertainment branding at the [[Clive Davis Institute of Recorded Music]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tisch.nyu.edu/about/directory/clive-davis-institute/811700777.html|title=Maurice Bernstein|website=tisch.nyu.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Bernstein and Giant Step President Esther Yoon are frequently leveraged as subject matter experts in the areas of music and entertainment marketing, [[Luxury Retailers|luxury retail]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glossy.co/evolution-of-luxury/the-hamptons-are-a-summertime-hot-bed-for-luxury-retail|title=The Hamptons are a summertime hot bed for luxury retail|date=2016-07-19|website=Glossy|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> [[Experiential Marketing|experiential marketing]], and the experience economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.luxurydaily.com/announcing-luxury-firstlook-2017-time-for-luxury-2-0/|title=Announcing Luxury FirstLook 2017: Time for Luxury 2.0|last=reports|first=Staff|date=2016-10-04|website=Luxury Daily|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Both Bernstein and Yoon are also guest contributors to media outlets including ''[[HuffPost|Huffington Post]]'' and ''PSFK''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/why-immersion-matters-in-2017_b_58bda90ee4b0ec3d5a6ba120|title=Why Immersion Matters in 2017|last=Week|first=Advertising|last2=ContributorEditor|date=2017-03-06|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/04/music-industry-veteran-maurice-bernstein-on-the-fu.html|title=Music Industry Veteran Maurice Bernstein on the Future of Brand and Artist Partnerships|date=2017-04-24|website=pastemagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref name=\"Swant{{!}}December 13\"/>\n\n== Company Expansion and Partners ==\n\n=== Esther Yoon ===\nEsther Yoon, a marketing executive and alum of consumer brands including [[Red Bull]] and [[Pinkberry]], joined Giant Step as a consultant in 2012, working alongside Bernstein to scale the agency\u2019s marketing and production capabilities. Yoon became a partner in Giant Step Marketing and was named President in 2014.<ref name=\"Swant{{!}}December 13\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/esthermyoon/|title=Esther Yoon - LinkedIn Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n=== Knitting Factory Entertainment ===\nGiant Step Marketing engaged in a partnership with Knitting Factory Entertainment in 2015. Knitting Factory, an organization historically known for its concert venues in New York and Los Angeles, has expanded into a twenty unit multiple tiered operation and portfolio company with over $40 million a year in revenue and 600 employees nationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/meet-the-top-10-entrepreneurs-and-their-companies-to-look-out-for-in-2019-300899321.html|title=Meet the Top 10 Entrepreneurs and Their Companies to Look Out for in 2019|last=Group|first=Imperium|website=prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ampthemag.com/the-real/knitting-factory-entertainment-expands-consulting-group/|title=Knitting Factory Entertainment Expands With Consulting Group|date=2016-11-02|website=Amplify|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7511013/knitting-factory-spaceland-presents|title=Knitting Factory Acquires 49 Percent Stake in Indie Promoter Spaceland: Exclusive|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n=== AuDigent ===\nGiant Step Marketing invested in AuDigent\u2019s \u201cfriends and family\u201d round for a stake in the company in 2016. AuDigent, a Philadelphia-based ad tech startup, expanded into an audience and data platform built around the music, entertainment, sports, and pop culture verticals with exclusive audience data segments from major record labels, influencers, and some of the world\u2019s largest content publishers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://technical.ly/philly/2016/05/16/jon-gosier-audigent-music-biz/|title=Jon Gosier's new adtech startup launches today at the Nashville Music Biz expo|last=contributor|first=Roberto Torres /|date=2016-05-16|website=Technical.ly Philly|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|title=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://audigent.com/|title=AuDigent {{!}} Audience Banking|website=audigent.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n\n=== Logo ===\nAfter seeing an ad in the newspaper in 1992, [[Rhode Island School of Design]] graduate, Kevin Lyons knocked on the door of Giant Step's offices.  There he met Bernstein and Rudnick who were impressed with his sketchbook and gave him a shot at designing Giant Step\u2019s [[logo]]. The opportunity \u201copened lots of doors\u201d for Lyons,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.1xrun.com/kevin-lyons-rolls-bakers-dozen-detroit-inner-state-gallery/|title=Kevin Lyons Rolls Out Baker\u2019s Dozen In Detroit With Inner State Gallery |last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> who went on to become a celebrated artist, creating products with [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Adidas]], [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]], [[Vans]], [[Uniqlo]] and Colette, among others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.naturalborn.com/work/info-2.php|title=Kevin Lyons|website=naturalborn.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Giant Step\u2019s logo has been named among the most \"iconic\" in New York music history, alongside the logos of [[Def Jam]], [[Ramones|the Ramones]], [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], and [[CBGB]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://daily.redbullmusicacademy.com/2013/06/iconic-logos|title=Red Bull Music Academy Daily|website=daily.redbullmusicacademy.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The logo is still used today.<ref>{{cite web|last=Forde|first=Laura|title=22 Iconic Music Logos Explained|url=http://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/magazine/iconic-logos|publisher=Red Bull Music Academy|accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Anthony Bourdain ===\nThe original Giant Step party from the early 1990s is referenced in the late Anthony Bourdain\u2019s bestselling memoir ''Kitchen Confidential: Adventures in the Culinary Underbelly'' (2000)'''''.'''''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Kitchen Confidential: Adventures in the Culinary Underbelly|last=Bourdain|first=Anthony|publisher=|year=2000|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n=== No Sleep ===\nGiant Step is featured in a dedicated section of DJ Stretch Armstrong and hip hop historian Evan Auerbach\u2019s 2016 book ''No Sleep: NYC Nightlife Flyers 1988-1999'', a visual history documenting New York nightlife between the late 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=No Sleep: NYC Nightlife Flyers 1988-1999|last=Bartos|first=Adrian|publisher=|year=2016|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In the book\u2019s introduction by [[Mark Ronson]], the original Giant Step club night is described as the \u201choly grail of hip New York\u201d at the time.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/shawnsetaro/2017/01/30/stretch-armstrong-evan-auerbach-no-sleep/|title='No Sleep' Shows The Artistic Side Of NYC Nightlife|last=Setaro|first=Shawn|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Giant Step Presents (2012 to present day) ===\nGiant Step continues to present different iterations of its original party under the \u201cGiant Step Presents\u201d banner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.giantstep.net/news-1|title=NEWS|website=GIANT STEP MARKETING|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Giant Step was revived as a seasonal party at Le Bain in New York from 2013 to 2018, featuring DJs such as [[Questlove]], Rich Medina, [[Ron Trent]], Danny Krivit and [[King Britt]].[[Giant Step#cite%20note-GiantStep-19|<sup>[19]</sup>]]<ref name=\"Standard\" /> In 2012, Giant Step partnered with [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]] to present the Offline Party series in New York.[[Giant Step#cite%20note-RA-44|<sup>[44]</sup>]] On why he chose to partner with Giant Step, Q-Tip cited that \u201ctheir brand and their quality are unmatched.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/clubs-nightlife/q-tip-helms-the-offline-party-at-irving-plaza|title=Q-Tip helms the Offline party at Irving Plaza|website=Time Out New York|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>  Giant Step continues to present an annual summer concert in New York\u2019s Central Park, as a part of the [[Central Park]] Summer Stage series.[[Giant Step#cite%20note-GiantStep-19|<sup>[19]</sup>]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.giantstep.net Official site]\n\n{{Portalbar|Companies}}\n\n[[Category:Advertising agencies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:American record labels]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 1995]]\n[[Category:House music record labels]]\n[[Category:Events in New York City]]\n[[Category:Branding companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Marketing companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the album by the musician Taj Mahal|Giant Step/De Ole Folks at Home}}\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name = Giant Step\n| image = [[File:Giant Step logo.png]]\n| image_bg = \n| parent = \n| founded = 1990\n| founder = Maurice Bernstein, \nJonathan Rudnick (1990-2001)\n| status = Active\n| distributor = \n| country = {{Flag|USA}}\n| location = [[New York City]], [[Los Angeles]]\n| url = http://www.giantstep.net/\n}}\n\n'''Giant Step''' is a media, events and marketing company headquartered in [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"facebook about\">{{cite web|title=Giant Step About|url=https://www.facebook.com/giantstep/info|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>   The company formerly released music through its [[record label]], Giant Step Records.<ref name=\"Jazz Times\">{{cite web|last=Terrell|first=Tom|title=Label Watch: Giant Step|url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/24721-label-watch-giant-step|publisher=Jazz Times|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=December 1997}}</ref> Giant Step is divided into two entities - the Giant Step brand, which promotes music and the creative agency, Giant Step Marketing, which provides marketing services to consumer brands.<ref name=linkedin>{{cite web|title=Giant Step Service|url=http://www.linkedin.com/company/giant-step/products?trk=top_nav_products|publisher=linkedin|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== The Groove Academy and early years ===\nGroove Academy began in 1990 as a party in [[New York City]].  The party was a weekly production of [[British people|British]] promoter, Maurice Bernstein, and his South African partner, Jonathan Rudnick.<ref name=grooveacademy>{{cite web|title=Groove Academy|url=http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/groove-academy|publisher=Giant Step|accessdate=20 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220060930/http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/groove-academy/|archive-date=20 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=Standard>{{cite web|title=A New York Tale: Giant Step|url=http://www.standardculture.com/posts/7804-A-New-York-Tale-Giant-Step|publisher=The Standard Culture|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=1 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131108234137/http://www.standardculture.com/posts/7804-A-New-York-Tale-Giant-Step|archive-date=8 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Initially unable to secure a loan from the bank, the pair borrowed money and used it to book acts and venues.<ref name=Winehouse/>  \u201cThe stars of the 70\u2019s, although they were highly sampled, were not getting recognition and were not being presented in a live forum,\u201d recalls Rudnick.<ref name=\"Jazz Times\" /> The two called their events, Groove Academy with its slogan, \u201cDedicated to the preservation of Funk.\u201d<ref>Mead, Rebecca, \"The Brit Pack,\" ''New York Magazine''. August 26, 1991, p. 111</ref><ref name=BritPack>{{cite journal|last=Mead|first=Rebecca|title=The Brit Pack|journal=New York Magazine|date=26 August 1991|pages=111}}</ref>\n\nBernstein recalled, \u201cThe first Groove Academy shows were put on by literally looking up artists in the [[telephone book]] \u2026 None of them had [[Music Booking Agent|agents]] then, we\u2019d just call them up at home and say \u2018are you interested in doing a show with us?\u2019[[Giant Step#cite%20note-DJ%20History-38|<sup>[38]</sup>]] The two called their events Groove Academy with its slogan, \u201cDedicated to the preservation of Funk\u201d and began rediscovering musicians whose records they had collected as teenagers. <sup>[10][[Giant Step#cite%20note-9|[9]]][[Giant Step#cite%20note-BritPack-10|[10]]]</sup>\n\nThe events were extended onto the dance floor under the new name Giant Step, after the fabled [[John Coltrane]] album ''[[Giant Steps]]''.<ref name=\"Winehouse\">{{cite web|last=Furman|first=Phyllis|title=Tribeca promoter's business creates buzz; helps launch Amy Winehouse |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/2.1353/tribeca-promoter-business-creates-buzz-helps-launch-amy-winehouse-article-1.285069|publisher=Daily News|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=2 March 2008}}</ref> The Giant Step party differentiated itself from Groove Academy with its emphasis on mixing [[Jazz]] and [[Hip Hop]]. Giant Step would soon go on tour around the States, [[Europe]] and [[Japan]].<ref name=\"djhistory\">{{cite web|title=Giant Step Company|url=http://www.djhistory.com/features/giant-step-1996|publisher=DJ History|accessdate=20 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109021634/http://www.djhistory.com/features/giant-step-1996|archive-date=9 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Giant Step party (1990s to early 2000's) ===\nThe Giant Step party started off as a weekly event that mixed live [[jazz]] and [[hiphop]]. While The Groove Academy staged concerts with [[Maceo Parker]], [[Isaac hayes|Isaac Hayes]], [[The Ohio Players]] and [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]],[[Giant Step#cite%20note-DJ%20History-38|<sup>[38]</sup>]] Bernstein and Rudnick extended onto the dancefloor with their Giant Step party. Greatly influenced by the [[acid jazz]] club-nights in [[England]], like [[Gilles Peterson|Gilles Peterson\u2019s]] [[Talkin' Loud|Talkin' Loud And Sayin' Something]],.[[Giant Step#cite%20note-DJ%20History-38|<sup>[38]</sup>]][[Giant Step#cite%20note-Acid%20Jazz%20Defines%20Cool-39|<sup>[39]</sup>]] Giant Step offered a stage where visiting [[rappers]] and jazz musicians, along with the regular Giant Step band, improvised to prerecorded [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]] and funk.[[Giant Step#cite%20note-40|<sup>[40]</sup>]] Giant Step hold as emerging acid jazz artists, like the [[Digable Planets]], [[The Brand New Heavies]] and [[Jamiroquai]], launched their stateside careers here.[[Giant Step#cite%20note-41|<sup>[41]</sup>]] Many other notable artists debuted at Giant Step shows as well including [[The Fugees]] and [[Massive Attack]].[[Giant Step#cite%20note-cielo-42|<sup>[42]</sup>]] The party originally took place at S.O.B.\u2019s but later moved to other venues such as Metropolis Caf\u00e9, Supper Club, Shine, New Music Caf\u00e9 and [[the Village Gate]].[[Giant Step#cite%20note-throwback-43|<sup>[43]</sup>]] In 2002 the weekly party was discontinued. Later the Giant Step party would be re-launched at the [[Hudson Hotel]]. Giant Step\u2019s events expanded into select markets outside of New York City, including shows in Los Angeles, [[Miami]], [[Chicago]] and [[Washington DC]].[[Giant Step#cite%20note-gsevents-37|<sup>[37]</sup>]] \n\n=== Record label ===\nAs the events continued to expand in the mid 90s, Giant Step moved into management, signing Dana Bryant, [[Repercussions (band)]], and [[Groove Collective]], securing record deals for the three on [[Warner Brothers]].<ref name=\"Jazz Times\"/> Other artists managed include [[Raw Stylus]], whom Giant Step signed to [[Geffen Records]].<ref name=Standard/> During this time Giant Step worked with [[Gary Katz]], best known for his work with [[Steely Dan]], to help produce the albums for [[Groove Collective]], [[Repercussions (band)]] and [[Raw Stylus]].<ref name=trouserpress>{{cite web|title=Groove Collective: Gary Katz|url=http://www.trouserpress.com/entry.php?a=groove_collective|publisher=Trouser Press|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>    In 1995, record producer Tommy Lipuma took over [[GRP Records]] at [[MCA Records]] and invited Giant Step to set up there as an imprint label.  The first act to be signed to the label was the jazz group, [[Groove Collective]].<ref name=Standard/>\n\nIn early 1997, Giant Step achieved acclaim for their work with ''[[Nuyorican Soul]]'' and a partnership with [[Gilles Peterson]]\u2019s label, Talkin Loud.<ref name=discogs>{{cite web|title=Nuyorican Soul|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/2267-Nuyorican-Soul|publisher=Discogs|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>   The group was a collaboration between Latin house DJs, [[Little Louie Vega|\u201cLittle\u201d Louie Vega]] and [[Kenny \"Dope\" Gonzalez|Kenny \u201cDope\u201d Gonzales]], who were also commonly known as [[Masters at Work]].  Nuyorican Soul featured many real musicians as opposed to sampled or synthesized sounds. Musicians who took part in the project included [[George Benson]], [[Tito Puente]], [[Roy Ayers]], [[DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince|Jazzy Jeff]], [[Jocelyn Brown]], and salsa queen, India.<ref name=LATimes>{{cite web|last=Ali|first=Lorraine|title=Soul Men, 'Nuyorican' Style|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/jul/27/entertainment/ca-16575|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=27 July 1997}}</ref> Three singles from the first Nuyorican Soul album made it to the top of the [[Billboard Hot 100|Billboard Charts;]] \u201c[[Runaway (Nuyorican Soul song)|Runaway]]\u201d, \u201cYou Can Do It (Baby)\u201d and \u201cI Am The Black Gold Of The Sun.\u201d<ref name=\"Jazz Times\"/> The album, released in March 2007, sold over 50,000 units by the end of July the same year.<ref name=LATimes/> [[Epic Records]] soon approached Bernstein and Rudnick with an offer.<ref name=Standard/>  Although Giant Step was a music label, [[Epic Records]] was primarily interested in Giant Step\u2019s marketing capabilities and offered the company a retainer contract where their record label was a secondary priority.<ref name=Standard/>\n\n=== Music marketing and label discontinuation ===\nFor their first project with [[Epic Records]], Giant Step helped launch the career of [[Macy Gray]], followed by [[Jill Scott]] and the re-launch of [[Sade (band)|Sade]].<ref name=Standard/> The company promoted [[Macy Gray]] by getting her music played in caf\u00e9s, clubs, and restaurants. According to Rose Noone, VP of [[A&R]] at [[Epic Records]], the music was \u201cheard everywhere.\u201d<ref name=Standard/>   Giant Step went on to help [[Def Jam Records]] artist [[Musiq Soulchild]] by pushing his music in untapped markets.<ref name=RecordBreakers/>  The previously unknown singer sold 55,000 copies of his debut album in its first week.<ref name=RecordBreakers>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Ethan|title=Music: Record Breakers|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/music/features/4200/|publisher=New York Magazine|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nAlthough, Giant Step Records released a [[Gilles Peterson]] compilation with [[Epic Records]], Bernstein and Rudnick eventually grew frustrated with having an [[Imprint label|imprint deal]].<ref name=Standard/>  Corporate management denied their requests to sign artists like [[India Arie]] and Donnie, and so in 2000, Giant Step decided to start their own label.<ref name=Winehouse/> However the following year,  Rudnick would leave company to pursue other interests.<ref name=Winehouse/> With money received from Epic, Bernstein started work on a series of tracks with singer, Donnie, that would eventually become the album, ''Welcome to the Colored Section''.  Steve \u201cThe Scotman\u201d Harvey was enlisted as the [[Music producer|producer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Colored Section|url=http://stevethescotsmanharvey.bandcamp.com/album/the-colored-section|publisher=Steve The Scotsman Harvey|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref> Singles from this album include, \u201cDo You Know\u201d and \u201cCloud9\u201d.<ref name=donnie/>  ''Welcome to the Colored Section'' was called \u201cthe best soul record since Stevie Wonder's masterpieces of the 1970s,\" by the ''Boston Globe''.<ref name=donnie>{{cite web|title=Donnie|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/donnie-1|publisher=Answers.com|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>   The independent success of ''Welcome to the Colored Section'', brought a joint venture with [[Motown Records]] and private investment into the label.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cannick|first=Jasmyne|title=Donnie on Life After Motown and The Colored Section, the New Album, and His Newfound Freedom|url=http://jasmynecannick.typepad.com/jasmynecannickcom/2007/07/the-daily-news-.html|publisher=Jasmyne Cannick|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=July 2007}}</ref> Giant Step has also released albums for [[Carl Hancock]], [[Gilles Peterson]], Turntables on the Hudson, [[Ultra Nate]], [[Zero 7]], [[Jody Watley]], Donnie, Sara Devine, [[Jiva]] and [[Zap Mama]].<ref name=\"GiantStep\">{{cite web|url=http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/events/|title=Giant Step Events|publisher=Giant Step|accessdate=8 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206123332/http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/events/|archive-date=6 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHowever the venture had many operating issues.  Its financial troubles threatened Giant Step\u2019s marketing business and the company nearly shut down. After an expected second round of investment didn't come through, the label ground to a halt in 2005.<ref name=Winehouse/> With the record label closed, Giant Step focused its efforts on developing their marketing business.<ref name=Standard/>  Giant Step soon entered a collaboration with [[Sade (singer)|Sade]], and helped the artist sell 400,000 copies of her album during its first week in stores.<ref name=RecordBreakers/> In 2006, Universal Republic Records hired Giant Step to promote then-unknown [[Amy Winehouse]] - the company's grassroots campaign was acknowledge for supporting Winehouse's cross over into the mainstream in 2007.<ref name=\"Winehouse\" /> Other notable artists that were launched through Giant Step's music marketing program include [[Lady Gaga]], [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]] and [[Adele]].<ref name=GSM>{{cite web|title=Giant Step Marketing|url=http://www.giantstepmarketing.net/}}</ref>\n\n== Creative agency era ==\n\n=== 2000s ===\nAfter an initial foray with [[Levi's]] Miles Ahead Music Series and [[LG]], Giant Step expanded into [[brand marketing]] with their [[creative agency]], Giant Step Marketing.<ref name=\"RecordBreakers\" /> The company\u2019s work with the [[Levi\u2019s]] Miles Ahead Series debuted [[Jill Scott]], [[Air (French band)|Air]] and [[Massive Attack]].<ref name=\"RecordBreakers\" /> The series also featured bands such as [[Femi Kuti]], [[Kruder & Dorfmeister]], [[Fatboy Slim]], [[Morcheeba]], [[Bebel Gilberto]] and [[Terry Callier]].  For [[LG]], the agency coordinated press outreach, online promotions, and venues to help launch [[LG]]\u2019s new mobile phone line.  Events included performances by [[Jurassic 5]], [[Thievery Corporation]], [[The Pharcyde]], [[Zero 7]], [[Van Hunt]], [[Miss Kittin]], [[Raphael Saadiq]] and [[Everything But The Girl]].<ref name=\"Siegel\">{{cite web|title=GIANT STEP - LG MOBILE PHONES|url=http://lyndsaysiegel.com/project.php?currentpage=7|publisher=Lyndsay Siegel|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2007 and 2011 Giant Step Marketing produced music events for [[Ian Schrager]]'s [[Morgans Hotel Group]].<ref name=\"GiantStep\" /> This series included two years of [[Grammy]] and [[Fashion week]] events and featured artists such as [[The Roots]], [[Common (artist)|Common]], [[Grace Jones]], [[Erykah Badu]], [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]], [[Estelle (musician)|Estelle]], [[De La Soul]] and [[The Kills]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Morgans Hotel Group Announces New Music Series With Giant Step at Hudson in 2008: 'Monday Nights at Hudson'|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=194863&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1110492&highlight=|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131108225354/http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=194863&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1110492&highlight=|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-11-08|publisher=Corporate IR}}</ref>  In 2009, [[Svedka]] was brought in as a sponsor and the programs were expanded into the Svedka Future Music Series.<ref name=\"svedka\">{{cite web|title=Svedka Future Music Series|url=http://92bpm.com/2009/11/svedka-vodka-soda-with-twist-of-future.html|publisher=92BPM|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>  Notable musicians featured in the series include [[Robyn]], [[Wale (rapper)|Wale]], [[Mark Ronson]], [[N.E.R.D.]], [[Fitz & the Tantrums]], [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]] and [[Daft Punk]].<ref name=\"Svedka\">{{cite web|title=Svedka Vodka Giant Step|url=http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/svedka-vodka/|publisher=Giant Step|accessdate=8 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109005739/http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/svedka-vodka/|archive-date=9 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2008-2011 Giant Step Marketing launched [[Steve Madden (company)|Steve Madden]] Music.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Madden Music|url=http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/steve-madden-music/|access-date=2013-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109012510/http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/tag/steve-madden-music/|archive-date=2013-11-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> The company created branded content, executed [[social media]] and online [[publicity]] campaigns and produced an experiential marketing program that aligned the brand with artists such as [[Katy Perry]], [[Lady Gaga]], K\u2019Naan, [[Katy B]] and [[Melanie Fiona]].<ref name=\"Madden\">{{cite web|title=Steve Madden Music Summer Series Continues with FreeSol at Le Bain, 8/15|url=http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/2011/08/steve-madden-music-summer-series-continues-with-freesol-at-le-bain-815/|publisher=Giant Step|accessdate=8 November 2013|date=9 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109005742/http://www.giantstep.net/index.php/2011/08/steve-madden-music-summer-series-continues-with-freesol-at-le-bain-815/|archive-date=9 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable campaigns (2011 and beyond) ===\nIn 2011, Giant Step worked with music producer [[David Guetta]] to create awareness for [[The Coca-Cola Company|Coca-Cola]]\u2019s energy drink, Burn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vimeo.com/61142143|title=David Guetta, Nothing But The Beat|publisher=Giant Step Marketing|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref> Later in 2011 Giant Step Marketing promoted the launch of [[Barneys New York]]\u2019s \u201cGaga\u2019s Workshop,\u201d a holiday collaboration with [[Lady Gaga]]. The company provided [[Public relations|PR]], [[social media]], digital and experiential campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swpnyc.com/2013/10/barneys-and-lady-gagas-workshop/|title=Gaga's Workshop}}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Giant Step Marketing launched Absolut X for [[Absolut Vodka]], a multi-year, integrated marketing program aimed at pairing music, art, & cocktails together.<ref name=\"absolutabout\">{{cite web|title=About Absolut X|url=http://absolutx.com/about|publisher=Absolut Vodka|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>  The program included 6 events in major markets in the form of a [[masquerade ball]], content, traditional advertising and a digital campaign.<ref name=\"absolutevents\">{{cite web|title=Absolut X Events|url=http://absolutx.com/events/|publisher=Absolut Vodka|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref> The experiential program won a gold Ex Award in 2013 (\"Best Production of An Event\") and garnered media coverage from national media outlets.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE BEST OF THE BEST IN 2013|url=http://emsummit.eventmarketer.com/exawards/|publisher=Event Marketing Summit|access-date=2013-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131123054958/http://emsummit.eventmarketer.com/exawards/|archive-date=2013-11-23|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Block|first=Tracy|title=Absolut X Blends Cocktails, Art, and Music at Miami Masquerade Tour Stop |url=http://www.bizbash.com/absolut-x-blends-cocktails-art-and-music-at-miami-masquerade-tour-stop/miami/story/26188/#sthash.JEEWjcg4.dpbs|publisher=BizBash|date=30 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nGiant Step Marketing produced and promoted the \"Music Experiment 2.0\" concert series in 2013 for [[Intel]] and [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]. The series featured artists such as [[Arcade Fire]], [[Empire of the Sun (band)|Empire of the Sun]] and [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]] and was broadcast on MTV Iggy and via livestream; the Arcade Fire show was also broadcast on \"[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]\" in partnership with ABC.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music Experiment 2.0|url=http://www.residentadvisor.net/event.aspx?504580}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theknow.denverpost.com/2013/10/30/watch-arcade-fire-on-jimmy-kimmel/80071/|title=Watch: Arcade Fire on Jimmy Kimmel, performing on the Capitol Records building|date=2013-10-30|website=The Know|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2013/10/arcade-fire-capitol-records-reflektor-kimmel/|title=See Arcade Fire Preach Outside the Capitol Records Building for \u2018Kimmel\u2019|date=2013-10-30|website=Spin|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The Intel series was later recognized with a silver [[Clio Awards|Clio Award]] in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clios.com/awards/winner/clio-music-integrated-campaign/intel-presents-the-music-experiment-powered-by-mtv-3336|title=- Intel Presents The Music Experiment, Powered by MTV Iggy|website=Clios|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Giant Step Marketing worked with [[Western Union]] to create a viral holiday campaign that would surprise real customers. The stunt was staged and filmed in Western Union\u2019s Times Square location, where customers were called in under the guise of \u201cbusiness,\u201d only to be greeted with a custom tent, decorated with family and country mementos, and their favorite home cooked meal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/steveolenski/2014/12/12/western-union-cooks-up-memories-for-the-holidays/|title=Western Union Cooks Up Memories For The Holidays|last=Olenski|first=Steve|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The campaign was credited for aiding in the \u201c[skyrocketing] of social engagement at Western Union,\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/western-union-karen-obrien/|title=How Social Engagement Skyrocketed at Western Union|last=Cohen{{!}}April 27|first=David|last2=2016 .aw-st0{fill:#F7EC13}.aw-st1{clip-path:url}.aw-st2{clip-path:url;fill:#020100}|website=adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> and recognized with a [[Shorty Awards|Shorty Award]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shortyawards.com/7th/wuhomecooked|title=#WUHomeCooked - The Shorty Awards|website=shortyawards.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nBernstein was tapped by [[Samsung Electronics|Samsung Electronics America]] in 2015 to serve as interim General Manager of its planned flagship experience center, and to oversee the opening of the building. Bernstein and Giant Step Marketing operated as Samsung\u2019s in-house agency, with the sole focus of launching Samsung 837 in 2016.<ref name=\"Swant{{!}}December 13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/agencies/new-york-shop-takes-jazz-approach-marketing-and-events-175020/|title=This New York Shop Takes a Jazz-like Approach to Marketing and Events|last=Swant{{!}}December 13|first=Marty|last2=2016 .aw-st0{fill:#F7EC13}.aw-st1{clip-path:url}.aw-st2{clip-path:url;fill:#020100}|website=adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://it-list.eventmarketer.com/?q=winner-158|title=Event Marketer - GIANT STEP:GIANT STEP|website=It List 2019|language=en-us|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> A first of its kind building in the heart of the Meatpacking District in Manhattan, Samsung 837 is home to concerts, cultural events, screenings and immersive experiences.<ref name=\"Warren\">{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2016/02/20/samsung-837-flagship/|title=Inside Samsung 837: Samsung's first North American flagship|last=Warren|first=Christina|website=Mashable|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The building, which has been recognized as a forerunner in the [[experiential retail]] category and was awarded \u201cBest Store Design of the Year,\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.designretailonline.com/news/awards-events/samsung-837-wins-best-store-design-of-the-year/|title=Samsung 837 wins Best Store Design of the Year|website=design:retail|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> showcases Samsung\u2019s technology in all of its programming.<ref name=\"Warren\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Giant Step Marketing was engaged by [[W Hotels]] and [[Marriott International]] to develop an integrated music platform, which eventually became W Records, the world\u2019s first-ever hotel music label.<ref name=\"Wang\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jennawang/2018/10/09/w-hotels-launches-first-ever-hotel-music-label/|title=W Hotels Launches First-Ever Hotel Music Label|last=Wang|first=Jenna|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref name=\"Wang\"/> In its first year, W Records signed and released new music from artists such as Amber Mark, [[Perfume Genius]], Roosevelt and [[Japanese Breakfast]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.marriott.com/2019/04/mic-drop-w-records-announces-japanese-breakfast-final-artist-in-the-programs-inaugural-class/|title=Mic Drop: W Records Announces Japanese Breakfast, Final Artist in the Program\u2019s Inaugural Class|date=2019-04-26|website=Marriott News Center|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> In September 2019, Giant Step was recognized with a bronze [[Clio Awards|Clio Award]] for W Records, in the \u201cIntegrated Campaign\u201d category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clios.com/music/winner/integrated-campaign/w-hotels/w-records-61267|title=W Hotels - W Records|website=Clios|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to its integrated campaign work, Giant Step Marketing is frequently hired to produce high-profile concerts for consumer brands in various global markets, including the opening of the Times Square EDITION Hotel with [[Diana Ross]] and [[Nile Rodgers]], the launch of [[SoundCloud]] Go with [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Spotify|Spotify\u2019s]] Latin Grammy Awards party with [[J Balvin]], [[Daddy Yankee]] and [[Luis Fonsi]], and [[Lincoln Motor Company]]\u2019s concert series featuring [[Gary Clark Jr.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|title=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref name=\"Swant{{!}}December 13\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8039180/buchanans-spotify-latin-grammy-nominees-performances|title=Buchanan's and Spotify Celebrate Latin Grammy Nominees With Performances by Sebastian Yatra, Luis Fonsi, Vives and More|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7685076/gary-clark-jr-lincoln-motor-company-ad-grammys-cord-video|title=Gary Clark Jr. Teams With Lincoln Motor Company for New TV Spot 'Cord': Exclusive|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Giant Step Marketing has been named in ''Event Marketer''\u2019s annual \u201cIt List\u201d of the world\u2019s top 100 event agencies every year since 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/list/2014itlist/|title=2014 It List Archives - Event Marketer|website=eventmarketer.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/article/2015-list-check-industrys-top-100-event-agencies/|title=The 2015 It List is Here... Top 100 Event Agencies - Event Marketer|website=eventmarketer.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/2016-it-list/|title=The 2016 It List - Event Marketer|website=eventmarketer.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2017/|title=Event Marketer - The 2017 It List|website=2017 It List|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|title=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/article/the-2019-it-list/|title=The 2019 It List: Recognizing the Top 100 Event Agencies|website=eventmarketer.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>   \n\n=== Creative agency clients (past and present) ===\n[[Absolut Vodka|Absolut]] ([[Pernod Ricard]]), [[Adidas]], [[Bacardi]], [[Barneys New York]], [[Coca-Cola]], Clarks, EDITION Hotels, [[HBO]], [[HP Inc.]], [[Intel]], [[Levi Strauss & Co.|Levi's]], [[LG Corporation]], [[Marriott International]], [[Morgans Hotel Group]], [[MTV]] ([[Viacom International Media Networks|Viacom]]), [[Old Navy]], [[SoundCloud]], [[Spotify]], [[Sundance TV]], [[Lincoln Motor Company|The Lincoln Motor Company]], [[Red Bull]], [[Steve Madden (company)|Steve Madden]], [[Western Union]], [[W Hotels]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.giantstep.net|title=Giant Step client list|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Thought leadership ===\nBernstein joined the faculty at [[New York University Tisch School of the Arts]] in 2018, teaching music and entertainment branding at the [[Clive Davis Institute of Recorded Music]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tisch.nyu.edu/about/directory/clive-davis-institute/811700777.html|title=Maurice Bernstein|website=tisch.nyu.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Bernstein and Giant Step President Esther Yoon are frequently leveraged as subject matter experts in the areas of music and entertainment marketing, [[Luxury Retailers|luxury retail]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glossy.co/evolution-of-luxury/the-hamptons-are-a-summertime-hot-bed-for-luxury-retail|title=The Hamptons are a summertime hot bed for luxury retail|date=2016-07-19|website=Glossy|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> [[Experiential Marketing|experiential marketing]], and the experience economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.luxurydaily.com/announcing-luxury-firstlook-2017-time-for-luxury-2-0/|title=Announcing Luxury FirstLook 2017: Time for Luxury 2.0|last=reports|first=Staff|date=2016-10-04|website=Luxury Daily|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Both Bernstein and Yoon are also guest contributors to media outlets including ''[[HuffPost|Huffington Post]]'' and ''PSFK''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/why-immersion-matters-in-2017_b_58bda90ee4b0ec3d5a6ba120|title=Why Immersion Matters in 2017|last=Week|first=Advertising|last2=ContributorEditor|date=2017-03-06|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/04/music-industry-veteran-maurice-bernstein-on-the-fu.html|title=Music Industry Veteran Maurice Bernstein on the Future of Brand and Artist Partnerships|date=2017-04-24|website=pastemagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref name=\"Swant{{!}}December 13\"/>\n\n== Company Expansion and Partners ==\n\n=== Esther Yoon ===\nEsther Yoon, a marketing executive and alum of consumer brands including [[Red Bull]] and [[Pinkberry]], joined Giant Step as a consultant in 2012, working alongside Bernstein to scale the agency\u2019s marketing and production capabilities. Yoon became a partner in Giant Step Marketing and was named President in 2014.<ref name=\"Swant{{!}}December 13\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/esthermyoon/|title=Esther Yoon - LinkedIn Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n=== Knitting Factory Entertainment ===\nGiant Step Marketing engaged in a partnership with Knitting Factory Entertainment in 2015. Knitting Factory, an organization historically known for its concert venues in New York and Los Angeles, has expanded into a twenty unit multiple tiered operation and portfolio company with over $40 million a year in revenue and 600 employees nationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/meet-the-top-10-entrepreneurs-and-their-companies-to-look-out-for-in-2019-300899321.html|title=Meet the Top 10 Entrepreneurs and Their Companies to Look Out for in 2019|last=Group|first=Imperium|website=prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ampthemag.com/the-real/knitting-factory-entertainment-expands-consulting-group/|title=Knitting Factory Entertainment Expands With Consulting Group|date=2016-11-02|website=Amplify|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7511013/knitting-factory-spaceland-presents|title=Knitting Factory Acquires 49 Percent Stake in Indie Promoter Spaceland: Exclusive|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n=== AuDigent ===\nGiant Step Marketing invested in AuDigent\u2019s \u201cfriends and family\u201d round for a stake in the company in 2016. AuDigent, a Philadelphia-based ad tech startup, expanded into an audience and data platform built around the music, entertainment, sports, and pop culture verticals with exclusive audience data segments from major record labels, influencers, and some of the world\u2019s largest content publishers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://technical.ly/philly/2016/05/16/jon-gosier-audigent-music-biz/|title=Jon Gosier's new adtech startup launches today at the Nashville Music Biz expo|last=contributor|first=Roberto Torres /|date=2016-05-16|website=Technical.ly Philly|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|title=https://www.eventmarketer.com/it-list-2018/|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://audigent.com/|title=AuDigent {{!}} Audience Banking|website=audigent.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n\n=== Logo ===\nAfter seeing an ad in the newspaper in 1992, [[Rhode Island School of Design]] graduate, Kevin Lyons knocked on the door of Giant Step's offices.  There he met Bernstein and Rudnick who were impressed with his sketchbook and gave him a shot at designing Giant Step\u2019s [[logo]]. The opportunity \u201copened lots of doors\u201d for Lyons,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.1xrun.com/kevin-lyons-rolls-bakers-dozen-detroit-inner-state-gallery/|title=Kevin Lyons Rolls Out Baker\u2019s Dozen In Detroit With Inner State Gallery |last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> who went on to become a celebrated artist, creating products with [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Adidas]], [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]], [[Vans]], [[Uniqlo]] and Colette, among others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.naturalborn.com/work/info-2.php|title=Kevin Lyons|website=naturalborn.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Giant Step\u2019s logo has been named among the most \"iconic\" in New York music history, alongside the logos of [[Def Jam]], [[Ramones|the Ramones]], [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], and [[CBGB]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://daily.redbullmusicacademy.com/2013/06/iconic-logos|title=Red Bull Music Academy Daily|website=daily.redbullmusicacademy.com|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The logo is still used today.<ref>{{cite web|last=Forde|first=Laura|title=22 Iconic Music Logos Explained|url=http://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/magazine/iconic-logos|publisher=Red Bull Music Academy|accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Anthony Bourdain ===\nThe original Giant Step party from the early 1990s is referenced in the late Anthony Bourdain\u2019s bestselling memoir ''Kitchen Confidential: Adventures in the Culinary Underbelly'' (2000)'''''.'''''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Kitchen Confidential: Adventures in the Culinary Underbelly|last=Bourdain|first=Anthony|publisher=|year=2000|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n=== No Sleep ===\nGiant Step is featured in a dedicated section of DJ Stretch Armstrong and hip hop historian Evan Auerbach\u2019s 2016 book ''No Sleep: NYC Nightlife Flyers 1988-1999'', a visual history documenting New York nightlife between the late 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=No Sleep: NYC Nightlife Flyers 1988-1999|last=Bartos|first=Adrian|publisher=|year=2016|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In the book\u2019s introduction by [[Mark Ronson]], the original Giant Step club night is described as the \u201choly grail of hip New York\u201d at the time.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/shawnsetaro/2017/01/30/stretch-armstrong-evan-auerbach-no-sleep/|title='No Sleep' Shows The Artistic Side Of NYC Nightlife|last=Setaro|first=Shawn|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Giant Step Presents (2012 to present day) ===\nGiant Step continues to present different iterations of its original party under the \u201cGiant Step Presents\u201d banner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.giantstep.net/news-1|title=NEWS|website=GIANT STEP MARKETING|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Giant Step was revived as a seasonal party at Le Bain in New York from 2013 to 2018, featuring DJs such as [[Questlove]], Rich Medina, [[Ron Trent]], Danny Krivit and [[King Britt]].[[Giant Step#cite%20note-GiantStep-19|<sup>[19]</sup>]]<ref name=\"Standard\" /> In 2012, Giant Step partnered with [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]] to present the Offline Party series in New York.[[Giant Step#cite%20note-RA-44|<sup>[44]</sup>]] On why he chose to partner with Giant Step, Q-Tip cited that \u201ctheir brand and their quality are unmatched.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/clubs-nightlife/q-tip-helms-the-offline-party-at-irving-plaza|title=Q-Tip helms the Offline party at Irving Plaza|website=Time Out New York|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>  Giant Step continues to present an annual summer concert in New York\u2019s Central Park, as a part of the [[Central Park]] Summer Stage series.[[Giant Step#cite%20note-GiantStep-19|<sup>[19]</sup>]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External 